# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pneumatic-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] Ihde was born on December 31, 1909, in Neenah, Wisconsin to parents who were dairy farmers and second-generation German immigrants to the United States.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] He studied chemistry at the University of Wisconsin–Madison, where he graduated with a bachelor's degree in 1931.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] He then worked as a chemist at the Blue Valley Creamery Company in Chicago.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] In early 1938, he returned to the University of Wisconsin–Madison and studied food chemistry and biochemistry, receiving in 1941 his doctorate under Henry August Schuette (1885–1978) and Harry Steenbock.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] Schuette also awakened Ihde's interest in the history of chemistry.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] After teaching for the academic year 1941–1942 at Butler University in Indianapolis, Ihde became an instructor of chemistry at the University of Wisconsin–Madison 1942–1945; he was hired as a tenure-track assistant professor in 1945.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] He was eventually promoted to full professor and retired as professor emeritus in 1980.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] At the beginning of his career at UW Madison, he taught the introductory chemistry courses, but once on the tenure track, in 1946, he also revived the course on the history of chemistry which had been taught by Louis Kahlenberg until 1940.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] From 1947 until his retirement in 1980, Ihde taught an interdisciplinary course on "The Physical Universe".
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] For the academic year 1951–1952 he gave lectures at Havard University on the history of science at as a Carnegie Intern in General Education.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] At Harvard he came into contact with James B.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] In chemistry, Ihde was known for his work on the purity and safety of foods and pharmaceuticals.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] From 1955 to 1968, he was a member of the Wisconsin Food Standards Advisory Committee and chaired the committee for two years.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] In the early 1960s Ihde and other UW Madison professors, including Grant Cottam (1918–2009), James F.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] Hasler, Hugh Iltis, Karl Francis Schmidt (1922–2016), and Van Rensselaer Potter, advocated publicity for Rachel Carson’s *Silent Spring* and investigation of possible harmful effects of pesticides.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] His 1964 book *The Development of Modern Chemistry* was a standard work in the US for several decades.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] For many years, beginning in 1969, he was the editor of the newsletter *Badger Chemist*, as successor to Emory D.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] In addition to his chemistry professorship, in 1957 Ihde received a formal joint appointment as professor in UW Madison's department of the history of science.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] Stauffer (1913–1992), and Marshall Clagett were the primary founders of UW Madison's history of science department, which included a notable book collection on the early history of chemistry purchased by the university from Dexter Award-winning amateur historian of chemistry Denis Duveen.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] Ihde published on Paracelsus, Robert Boyle, Amedeo Avogadro, Michael Faraday, Robert Bunsen, and Adolf von Baeyer, on the history of chemistry in the United States, and on the history of pure food laws.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] He supervised the historian of chemistry and future Johns Hopkins University history of science department head Owen Hannaway's first position in the US in 1966.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] From 1962 to 1964 Ihde chaired the Division of History of the American Chemical Society (ACS).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] In 1963 he was elected a Fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] In 1968 Ihde received the Dexter Award of the Division of History of the ACS.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] In 1978 the University of Wisconsin honored him with the Chancellor's Award for Distinguished Teaching.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] In 1983 the ACS published a festschrift in his honor.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] In 2001 the first part of an issue of the *Bulletin for the History of Chemistry* was dedicated as a memorial to him.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] He died with advanced Alzheimer's disease in Sarasota, Florida on 23 February 2000.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/aaron-j-ihde] He was predeceased by his wife in 1988 and was survived by their son and daughter and several grandchildren.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Alchemists attempted to purify, mature, and perfect certain materials.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Common aims were chrysopoeia, the transmutation of "base metals" (e.g., lead) into "noble metals" (particularly gold); the creation of an elixir of immortality; and the creation of panaceas able to cure any disease.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The perfection of the human body and soul was thought to result from the alchemical *magnum opus* ("Great Work").
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The concept of creating the philosopher's stone was variously connected with all of these projects.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Islamic and European alchemists developed a basic set of laboratory techniques, theories, and terms, some of which are still in use today.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] They did not abandon the Ancient Greek philosophical idea that everything is composed of four elements, and they tended to guard their work in secrecy, often making use of cyphers and cryptic symbolism.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] In Europe, the 12th-century translations of medieval Islamic works on science and the rediscovery of Aristotelian philosophy gave birth to a flourishing tradition of Latin alchemy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] This late medieval tradition of alchemy would go on to play a significant role in the development of early modern science (particularly chemistry and medicine).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Modern discussions of alchemy are generally split into an examination of its exoteric practical applications and its esoteric spiritual aspects, despite criticisms by scholars such as Eric J.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Holmyard and Marie-Louise von Franz that they should be understood as complementary.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The former is pursued by historians of the physical sciences, who examine the subject in terms of early chemistry, medicine, and charlatanism, and the philosophical and religious contexts in which these events occurred.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The latter interests historians of esotericism, psychologists, and some philosophers and spiritualists.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The subject has also made an ongoing impact on literature and the arts.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The word alchemy comes from Old French *alkimie*, used in Medieval Latin as *alchymia*.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] This name was itself adopted from the Arabic word *al-kīmiyā* (الكيمياء).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The Arabic *al-kīmiyā* in turn was a borrowing of the Late Greek term *khēmeía* (χημεία), also spelled *khumeia* (χυμεία) and *khēmía* (χημία), with *al-* being the Arabic definite article 'the'.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Together this association can be interpreted as 'the process of transmutation by which to fuse or reunite with the divine or original form'.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Several etymologies have been proposed for the Greek term.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The first was proposed by Zosimos of Panopolis (3rd–4th centuries), who derived it from the name of a book, the *Khemeu*.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Hermann Diels argued in 1914 that it rather derived from χύμα, used to describe metallic objects formed by casting.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Others trace its roots to the Egyptian name *kēme*, meaning 'black earth', which refers to the fertile and auriferous soil of the Nile valley, as opposed to red desert sand.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] According to the Egyptologist Wallis Budge, the Arabic word **al-kīmiya*ʾ* actually means "the Egyptian [science]", borrowing from the Coptic word for "Egypt", **kēme** (or its equivalent in the Mediaeval Bohairic dialect of Coptic, **khēme**).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] This Coptic word derives from Demotic **kmỉ**, itself from ancient Egyptian **kmt**.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The ancient Egyptian word referred to both the country and the colour "black" (Egypt was the "black Land", by contrast with the "red Land", the surrounding desert).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Alchemy comprises a plurality of philosophical traditions extending across approximately four millennia and spanning three continents.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The marked tendency of these traditions toward esoteric and highly symbolic modes of expression renders it difficult to reconstruct their patterns of mutual influence and genealogical relationships.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Chinese alchemy was closely connected to Taoism and Indian alchemy with the Dharmic faiths.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In contrast, Western alchemy developed its philosophical system mostly independent of but influenced by various Western religions.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] It is still an open question whether these three strands share a common origin, or to what extent they influenced each other.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The start of Western alchemy may generally be traced to Hellenistic Egypt, where the city of Alexandria was a center of alchemical knowledge, and retained its pre-eminence through most of the Greek and Roman periods.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Following the work of André-Jean Festugière, modern scholars see alchemical practice in the Roman Empire as originating from the Egyptian goldsmith's art, Greek philosophy and different religious traditions.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Tracing the origins of the alchemical art in Egypt is complicated by the pseudepigraphic nature of texts from the Greek alchemical corpus.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The treatises of Zosimos of Panopolis, the earliest historically attested author (fl. c.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] 300), can help in situating the other authors.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Zosimus based his work on that of older alchemical authors, such as Mary the Jewess, Pseudo-Democritus, and Agathodaimon, but very little is known about any of these authors.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The most complete of their works, the *Four Books* of Pseudo-Democritus, were probably written in the first century AD.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Recent scholarship tends to emphasize the testimony of Zosimus, who traced the alchemical arts back to Egyptian metallurgical and ceremonial practices.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] It has also been argued that early alchemical writers borrowed the vocabulary of Greek philosophical schools but did not implement any of its doctrines in a systematic way.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Zosimos of Panopolis wrote in the *Final Abstinence* (a.k.a. the *Final Count*) that the ancient practice of "tinctures" (the technical Greek term for the alchemical arts) had been taken over by certain "demons" who taught the art only to those who offered them sacrifices.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Since Zosimos also called the demons "the guardians of places" (οἱ κατὰ τόπον ἔφοροι, *hoi katà tópon éphoroi*) and those who offered them sacrifices "priests" (ἱερέα, *hieréa*), it is fairly clear that he was referring to the gods of Egypt and their priests.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] While critical of the kind of alchemy he associated with the Egyptian priests and their followers, Zosimos nonetheless saw the tradition's recent past as rooted in the rites of the Egyptian temples.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Zosimos of Panopolis asserted that alchemy dated back to Pharaonic Egypt where it was the domain of the priestly class, though there is little to no evidence for his assertion.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Alchemical writers used classical figures from Greek (e.g., Hades), Roman (e.g., Lucius), and Egyptian mythology to illuminate their works and allegorize alchemical transmutation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] These included the pantheon of gods related to the classical planets, Isis, Osiris, Jason, and many others.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The central figure in the mythology of alchemy is Hermes Trismegistus (Ἑρμῆς ὁ Τρισμέγιστος, 'Hermes the Thrice-Greatest').
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] His name is derived from the god Thoth and his Greek counterpart, Hermes.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Hermes and his caduceus or serpent-staff, were among alchemy's principal symbols.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] According to Clement of Alexandria, he wrote what were called the "forty-two books of Hermes", covering all fields of knowledge.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The *Hermetica* are a compendium of texts attributed to Hermes Trismegistus.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Many of them have close historical connections with Western alchemical philosophy and practice (which was sometimes called the Hermetic philosophy by its practitioners).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] By modern convention, the *Hermetica* is usually subdivided into two main categories: the "technical" and "religio-philosophical" *Hermetica*.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The "technical" *Hermetica* deals with alchemy, astrology, medicine, pharmacology, and magic.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Its oldest parts were written in Greek and may go back as far as the second or third century BC.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Many of the texts in the "technical" *Hermetica* were later translated, first into Arabic and then into Latin, often being extensively revised and expanded throughout the centuries.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Some of them were also originally written in Arabic.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In other cases their status as an original work or translation remains unclear.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] These Arabic and Latin Hermetic texts were widely copied throughout the Middle Ages.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The most famous of these texts is the *Emerald Tablet*, also known as the *Smaragdine Table* or the *Tabula Smaragdina*, a compact and cryptic text.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The earliest known versions of it are four Arabic recensions preserved in mystical and alchemical treatises between the 8th and 10th centuries AD—chiefly the *Secret of Creation* (سر الخليقة, *Sirr al-Khalīqa*) and the *Secret of Secrets* (سرّ الأسرار, *Sirr al-Asrār*).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Medieval commentators such as Ortolanus interpreted it as a "foundational text" of alchemical instructions for producing the philosopher's stone and making gold.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The dawn of Western alchemy is sometimes associated with that of metallurgy, extending back to 3500 BC.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Many writings were lost when the Roman emperor Diocletian ordered the burning of alchemical books after suppressing a revolt in Alexandria (AD 292).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Few original Egyptian documents on alchemy have survived, most notable among them the Stockholm papyrus and the Leyden papyrus X.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Dating from AD 250 to 300, they contained recipes for dyeing and making artificial gemstones, cleaning and fabricating pearls, and manufacturing of imitation gold and silver.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] These writings lack the mystical, philosophical elements of alchemy, but do contain the works of Bolus of Mendes (or Pseudo-Democritus), which aligned these recipes with theoretical knowledge of astrology and the classical elements.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Between the time of Bolus and Zosimos, the change took place that transformed this metallurgy into a Hermetic art.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Alexandria acted as a melting pot for philosophies of Pythagoreanism, Platonism, Stoicism, and Gnosticism that formed the origin of alchemy's character.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] An important example of alchemy's roots in Greek philosophy, originated by Empedocles and developed by Aristotle, was that all things in the universe were formed from only four elements: earth, air, water, and fire.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] According to Aristotle, each element had a sphere to which it belonged and to which it would return if left undisturbed.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Later alchemists extensively developed the mystical aspects of this concept.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Alchemy coexisted alongside emerging Christianity.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Lactantius believed Hermes Trismegistus had prophesied its birth.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Augustine of Hippo later affirmed this in the 4th and 5th centuries, but also condemned Trismegistus for idolatry.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Examples of pagan, Christian, and Jewish alchemists can be found during this period.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Most of the Greco-Roman alchemists preceding Zosimos are known only by pseudonyms, such as Moses of Alexandria, Isis, Cleopatra the Alchemist, Pseudo-Democritus, and Ostanes.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Other authors such as Komarios and Chymes are known only through surviving fragments of text.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] After AD 400, Greek alchemical writers occupied themselves solely in commenting on the works of these predecessors.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] By the middle of the 7th century, alchemy was almost an entirely mystical discipline.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] It was at that time that Khalid Ibn Yazid sparked its migration from Alexandria to the Islamic world, facilitating the translation and preservation of Greek alchemical texts in the 8th and 9th centuries.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Greek alchemy was preserved in medieval Byzantine manuscripts after the fall of Roman Egypt, yet historians have only relatively recently begun to study and development of Greek alchemy in the Byzantine period.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The 2nd millennium BC Vedas describe a connection between eternal life and gold.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Buddhist texts from the 2nd to 5th centuries mention the transmutation of base metals to gold.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] According to some scholars Greek alchemy may have influenced Indian alchemy but there are no hard evidences to back this claim.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The goals of alchemy in India included the creation of a divine body (*divya-deham*) and immortality while still embodied (*jīvan-mukti*).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Sanskrit alchemical texts include much material on the manipulation of mercury and sulphur, that are homologized with the semen of the god Śiva and the menstrual blood of the goddess Devī.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Some early alchemical writings seem to have their origins in the Kaula tantric schools associated to the teachings of the personality of Matsyendranath.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Other early writings are found in the Jaina medical treatise *Kalyāṇakārakam* of Ugrāditya, written in South India in the early 9th century.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Two famous early Indian alchemical authors were Nāgārjuna Siddha and Nityanātha Siddha.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] His book *Rasendramangalam* is an example of Indian alchemy and medicine.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Nityanātha Siddha wrote *Rasaratnākara*, which was also a highly influential work.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In Sanskrit, *rasa* translates to "mercury", and Nāgārjuna Siddha was said to have developed a method of converting mercury into gold.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] An example of academic scholarship on Indian alchemy is *The Alchemical Body* by Indologist David Gordon White.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] A modern bibliography on Indian alchemical studies has been written by White.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The contents of 39 Sanskrit alchemical treatises have been analysed in detail in Gerrit Jan Meulenbeld's *History of Indian Medical Literature* (*HIML*).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The discussion of these works in the *HIML* gives a summary of the contents of each work, their special features, and where possible the evidence concerning their dating.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Chapter 13 of the *HIML*, *Various works on rasaśāstra and ratnaśāstra* ('Various works on alchemy and gems') gives brief details of another 655 treatises.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In some cases, Meulenbeld gives notes on the contents and authorship of these works; in other cases references are made only to the unpublished manuscripts of these titles.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] A great deal remains to be discovered about Indian alchemical literature.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] After the fall of the Roman Empire, the focus of alchemical development moved to the Islamic World.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Much more is known about Islamic alchemy because it was better documented: indeed, most of the earlier writings that have come down through the years were preserved as Arabic translations.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The word *alchemy* itself was derived from the Arabic word *al-kīmiyā* (الكيمياء).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The early Islamic world was a melting pot for alchemy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Platonic and Aristotelian thought, which had already been somewhat appropriated into Hermetic science, continued to be assimilated during the late 7th and early 8th centuries through Syriac translations and scholarship.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the late ninth and early tenth centuries, the Arabic works attributed to Jābir ibn Hayyān (Latinized as "Geber" or "Geberus") introduced a new approach to alchemy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Islamic philosophers also made great contributions to alchemical Hermeticism.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The most influential author in this regard was arguably ibn Hayyan. ibn Hayyan's ultimate goal was *takwin*, the artificial creation of life in the alchemical laboratory—up to and including human life.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] He analysed each Aristotelian element in terms of four basic qualities of *hotness*, *coldness*, *dryness*, and *moistness*.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] According to ibn Hayyan, in each metal two of these qualities were interior and two were exterior.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] For example, lead was externally cold and dry, while gold was hot and moist.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Thus, ibn Hayyan theorized, by rearranging the qualities of one metal, a different metal would result.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] By this reasoning, the search for the philosopher's stone was introduced to Western alchemy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Ibn Hayyan developed an elaborate numerology whereby the root letters of a substance's name in Arabic, when treated with various transformations, held correspondences to the element's physical properties.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The atomic theory of corpuscularianism, where all physical bodies possess an inner and outer layer of minute particles or corpuscles, also has its origins in the work of ibn Hayyan.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] From the 9th to 14th centuries, alchemical theories faced criticism from a variety of practical Muslim chemists, including Al-Kindi, Abū al-Rayhān al-Bīrūnī, Avicenna and Ibn Khaldun.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In particular, they wrote refutations against the idea of the transmutation of metals.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] From the 14th century onwards, many materials and practices originally belonging to Indian alchemy (*Rasayana*) were assimilated in the Persian texts written by Muslim scholars.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Researchers have found evidence that Chinese alchemists and philosophers discovered complex mathematical phenomena that were shared with Arab alchemists during the medieval period.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Discovered first in China before the Common Era, the "magic square of three" was propagated to followers of Jabir ibn Hayyan at some point over the proceeding several hundred years.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Other commonalities shared between the two alchemical schools of thought include discrete naming for ingredients and heavy influence from the natural elements.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The Silk Road provided a clear path for the exchange of goods, ideas, ingredients, religion, and many other aspects of life with which alchemy is intertwined.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Whereas European alchemy eventually centered on the transmutation of base metals into noble metals, Chinese alchemy had a more obvious connection to medicine.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The philosopher's stone of European alchemists can be compared to the elixir of life sought by Chinese alchemists.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the Hermetic view, these two goals were not unconnected, and the philosopher's stone was often equated with the universal panacea; therefore, the two traditions may have had more in common than initially appears.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] As early as 317 AD, Ge Hong documented the use of metals, minerals, and elixirs in early Chinese medicine.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Hong identified three ancient Chinese documents—titled the *Scripture of Great Clarity*, the *Scripture of the Nine Elixirs*, and the *Scripture of the Golden Liquor*—as texts containing fundamental alchemical information.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] He also described alchemy, along with meditation, as the sole spiritual practices that could allow one to gain immortality or to transcend to a higher state of being.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In his work *Inner Chapters of the Book of the Master Who Embraces Spontaneous Nature* (317 AD), Hong argued that alchemical solutions such as elixirs were preferable to traditional medicinal treatment due to the spiritual protection they could provide.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the centuries following Ge Hong's death, the emphasis placed on alchemy as a spiritual practice among Chinese Taoists was reduced.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In 499 AD, Tao Hongjing refuted Hong's statement that alchemy is as important a spiritual practice as Shangqing meditation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] While Hongjing did not deny the power of alchemical elixirs to grant immortality or provide divine protection, he ultimately found the *Scripture of the Nine Elixirs* to be ambiguous and spiritually unfulfilling, aiming to implement more accessible practising techniques.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the early 700s, *Neidan* (a.k.a. internal alchemy) was adopted by Daoists as a new form of alchemy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] *Neidan* emphasized appeasing the inner gods that inhabit the human body by practising alchemy with compounds naturally found in the body, rather than the mixing of natural resources that was so emphasized in early Dao alchemy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] For example, saliva was often considered nourishment for the inner gods and did not require any conscious alchemical reaction to produce.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The inner gods were not thought of as physical presences occupying each person, but rather a collection of deities that are each said to represent and protect a specific body part or region.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Although those who practised *Neidan* prioritized meditation over external alchemical strategies, many of the same elixirs and constituents from previous Daoist alchemical schools of thought continued to be utilized in tandem with meditation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Eternal life remained a consideration for *Neidan* alchemists, as it was believed that one would become immortal if an inner god were to be immortalized within them through spiritual fulfilment.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Chinese alchemy was closely connected to Taoist techniques in traditional Chinese medicine like acupuncture and moxibustion.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the early Song dynasty, followers of this Taoist idea—chiefly the elite and upper class—would ingest mercuric sulfide, which, though tolerable in low levels, led many to suicide.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The introduction of alchemy to Latin Europe may be dated to 11 February 1144, with the completion of Robert of Chester's translation of the *Liber de compositione alchemiae* (Book on the Composition of Alchemy) from an Arabic work attributed to Khalid ibn Yazid.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Although European craftsmen and technicians pre-existed, Robert notes in his preface that alchemy (here still referring to the elixir rather than to the art itself) was unknown in Latin Europe at the time of his writing.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The translation of Arabic texts concerning numerous disciplines including alchemy flourished in 12th-century Toledo, Spain, through contributors like Gerard of Cremona and Adelard of Bath.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Translations of the time included the Turba Philosophorum, and the works of Avicenna and Muhammad ibn Zakariya al-Razi.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] These brought with them many new words to the European vocabulary for which there was no previous Latin equivalent.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Alcohol, carboy, elixir, and athanor are examples.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Meanwhile, theologian contemporaries of the translators made strides towards the reconciliation of faith and experimental rationalism, thereby priming Europe for the influx of alchemical thought.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The 11th-century theologian Anselm of Canterbury put forth the opinion that faith and rationalism were compatible and encouraged rationalism in a Christian context.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the early 12th century, Peter Abelard followed Anselm's work, laying down the foundation for acceptance of Aristotelian thought before the first works of Aristotle had reached the West.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the early 13th century, Robert Grosseteste used Abelard's methods of analysis and added the use of observation, experimentation, and conclusions when conducting scientific investigations.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Grosseteste also did much work to reconcile Platonic and Aristotelian thinking.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Through much of the 12th and 13th centuries, alchemical knowledge in Europe remained centered on translations, and new Latin contributions were not made.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The efforts of the translators were succeeded by that of the encyclopaedists.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the 13th century, Albertus Magnus and Roger Bacon were the most notable of these, their work summarizing and explaining the newly imported alchemical knowledge in Aristotelian terms.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Albertus Magnus, a Dominican friar, is known to have written works such as the *Book of Minerals* where he observed and commented on the operations and theories of alchemical authorities like Hermes Trismegistus, pseudo-Democritus, and unnamed alchemists of his time.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Albertus critically compared these to the writings of Aristotle and Avicenna, where they concerned the transmutation of metals.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] From the time shortly after his death through to the 15th century, more than 28 alchemical tracts were misattributed to him, a common practice giving rise to his reputation as an accomplished alchemist.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Likewise, alchemical texts have been attributed to Albert's student Thomas Aquinas.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Bacon's writings integrated morality, salvation, alchemy, and the prolongation of life.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] His correspondence with Clement highlighted this, noting the importance of alchemy to the papacy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Like the Greeks before him, Bacon acknowledged the division of alchemy into practical and theoretical spheres.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] He noted that the theoretical lay outside the scope of Aristotle, the natural philosophers, and all Latin writers of his time.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The practical confirmed the theoretical, and Bacon advocated its uses in natural science and medicine.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In later European legend, he became an archmage.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In particular, along with Albertus Magnus, he was credited with the forging of a brazen head capable of answering its owner's questions.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Soon after Bacon, the influential work of Pseudo-Geber (sometimes identified as Paul of Taranto) appeared.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] His *Summa Perfectionis* remained a staple summary of alchemical practice and theory through the medieval and renaissance periods.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] It was notable for its inclusion of practical chemical operations alongside sulphur-mercury theory, and the unusual clarity with which they were described.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] By the end of the 13th century, alchemy had developed into a fairly structured system of belief.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Adepts believed in the macrocosm-microcosm theories of Hermes; namely, that processes that affect minerals and other substances could have an effect on the human body (for example, if one could learn the secret of purifying gold, one could use the technique to purify the human soul).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] They believed in the four elements and the four qualities as described above, and they had a strong tradition of cloaking their written ideas in a labyrinth of coded jargon set with traps to mislead the uninitiated.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Finally, the alchemists practised their art: they actively experimented with chemicals and made observations and theories about how the universe operated.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Their entire philosophy revolved around their belief that the human soul was divided within itself after the fall of Adam.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] By purifying the two parts of humankind's soul, humans could be reunited with God.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the 14th century, alchemy became more accessible to Europeans outside the confines of Latin-speaking churchmen and scholars.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Alchemical discourse shifted from scholarly philosophical debate to an exposed social commentary on the alchemists themselves.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Dante Alighieri, Piers Plowman, and Geoffrey Chaucer all painted unflattering pictures of alchemists as thieves and liars.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Pope John XXII's 1317 edict *Spondent quas non-exhibent* forbade the false promises of transmutation made by pseudo-alchemists.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Roman Catholic Inquisitor General Nicholas Eymerich's *Directorium Inquisitorum*, written in 1376, associated alchemy with the performance of demonic rituals, which Eymerich differentiated from magic performed in accordance with Christian scripture.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] This did not, however, lead to any change in the Inquisition's monitoring or prosecution of alchemists.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In 1404, Henry IV of England banned the practice of multiplying metals by the passing of the Gold and Silver Act 1403 (5 Hen.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] 4) (although it was possible to buy a licence to attempt to make gold alchemically, and a number were granted by Henry VI and Edward IV).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] These critiques and regulations centered more around pseudo-alchemical charlatanism than the actual study of alchemy, which continued with an increasingly Christian tone.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The 14th century saw the Christian imagery of death and resurrection employed in the alchemical texts of Petrus Bonus, John of Rupescissa, and in works written in the name of Raymond Lull and Arnold of Villanova.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Nicolas Flamel is a well-known alchemist to the point where he had many pseudepigraphic imitators.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Although the historical Flamel existed, the writings and legends assigned to him only appeared in 1612.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] A common idea in European alchemy in the medieval era was a metaphysical "Homeric chain of wise men that link[ed] heaven and earth" that included ancient pagan philosophers and other important historical figures.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] , meaning "redness", was adopted by alchemists and signalled alchemical success, and the end of the great work.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] During the Renaissance, Hermetic and Platonic foundations were restored to European alchemy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The dawn of medical, pharmaceutical, occult, and entrepreneurial branches of alchemy followed.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the late 15th century, Marsilio Ficino translated the Corpus Hermeticum and the works of Plato into Latin.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] These were previously unavailable to Europeans who for the first time had a full picture of the alchemical theory that Bacon had declared absent.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Renaissance Humanism and Renaissance Neoplatonism guided alchemists away from physics to refocus on mankind as the alchemical vessel.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Esoteric systems developed that blended alchemy into a broader occult Hermeticism, fusing it with magic, astrology, and Christian Kabbalah.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] A key figure in this development was Heinrich Cornelius Agrippa (1486–1535), a German who received his Hermetic education in Italy in the schools of the humanists.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In his *De Occulta Philosophia*, he attempted to merge Judaism's Kabbalah, Hermeticism, and alchemy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] He was instrumental in spreading this new blend of Hermeticism outside the borders of Italy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Paracelsus, born Philippus Aureolus Theophrastus Bombastus von Hohenheim (1493–1541), cast alchemy into a new form, rejecting some of Agrippa's occultism and moving away from chrysopoeia.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Paracelsus pioneered the use of chemicals and minerals in medicine and wrote, "Many have said of Alchemy, that it is for the making of gold and silver.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] His Hermetical views were that sickness and health in the body relied on the harmony of humankind as the microcosm and Nature the macrocosm.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] He took an approach different from those before him, using this analogy not in the manner of soul-purification but in the manner that humans must have certain balances of minerals in their bodies, and that certain illnesses of the body had chemical remedies that could cure them.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Iatrochemistry refers to the pharmaceutical applications of alchemy championed by Paracelsus.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] John Dee (13 July 1527 – December 1608) followed Agrippa's occult tradition.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Although better known for angel summoning, divination, and his role as astrologer, cryptographer, and consultant to Elizabeth I of England, Dee's alchemical *Monas Hieroglyphica*, written in 1564 was his most popular and influential work.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] His writing portrayed alchemy as a sort of terrestrial astronomy in line with the Hermetic axiom *as above, so below*.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] During the 17th century, a short-lived "supernatural" interpretation of alchemy became popular, including support by fellows of the Royal Society: Robert Boyle and Elias Ashmole.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Proponents of the supernatural interpretation of alchemy believed that the philosopher's stone might be used to summon and communicate with angels.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Entrepreneurial opportunities were common for the alchemists of Renaissance Europe.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Alchemists were contracted by the elite for practical purposes related to mining, medical services, and the production of chemicals, medicines, metals, and gemstones.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Rudolf II, Holy Roman Emperor, in the late 16th century, famously received and sponsored various alchemists at his court in Prague, including Dee and his associate Edward Kelley.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] King James IV of Scotland, Julius, Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg, Henry V, Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg, Augustus, Elector of Saxony, Julius Echter von Mespelbrunn, and Maurice, Landgrave of Hesse-Kassel all contracted alchemists.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] John's son Arthur Dee worked as a court physician to Michael I of Russia and Charles I of England but also compiled the alchemical book *Fasciculus Chemicus*.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Although most of these appointments were legitimate, the trend of pseudo-alchemical fraud continued through the Renaissance.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] *Betrüger* would use sleight of hand, or claims of secret knowledge to make money or secure patronage.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Legitimate mystical and medical alchemists such as Michael Maier and Heinrich Khunrath wrote about fraudulent transmutations, distinguishing themselves from the con artists.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] False alchemists were sometimes prosecuted for fraud.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The terms "chemia" and "alchemia" were used as synonyms in the early modern period, and the differences between alchemy, chemistry and small-scale assaying and metallurgy were not as neat as in the present day.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] There were important overlaps between practitioners, and trying to classify them into alchemists, chemists and craftsmen is anachronistic.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] For example, Tycho Brahe (1546–1601), an alchemist better known for his astronomical and astrological investigations, had a laboratory built at his Uraniborg observatory/research institute.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Michael Sendivogius (*Michał Sędziwój*, 1566–1636), a Polish alchemist, philosopher, medical doctor and pioneer of chemistry wrote mystical works but is also credited with distilling oxygen in a lab sometime around 1600.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Sendivogious taught his technique to Cornelius Drebbel who, in 1621, applied this in a submarine.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Isaac Newton devoted considerably more of his writing to the study of alchemy (see Isaac Newton's occult studies) than he did to either optics or physics.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Other early modern alchemists who were eminent in their other studies include Robert Boyle, and Jan Baptist van Helmont.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Their Hermeticism complemented rather than precluded their practical achievements in medicine and science.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The decline of European alchemy was brought about by the rise of modern science with its emphasis on rigorous quantitative experimentation and its disdain for "ancient wisdom".
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Although the seeds of these events were planted as early as the 17th century, alchemy still flourished for some two hundred years, and in fact may have reached its peak in the 18th century.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] As late as 1781 James Price claimed to have produced a powder that could transmute mercury into silver or gold.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Robert Boyle (1627–1691) pioneered the scientific method in chemical investigations.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] He assumed nothing in his experiments and compiled every piece of relevant data.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Boyle would note the place in which the experiment was carried out, the wind characteristics, the position of the Sun and Moon, and the barometer reading, all just in case they proved to be relevant.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] This approach eventually led to the founding of modern chemistry in the 18th and 19th centuries, based on revolutionary discoveries and ideas of Lavoisier and John Dalton.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Beginning around 1720, a rigid distinction began to be drawn for the first time between "alchemy" and "chemistry".
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] By the 1740s, "alchemy" was now restricted to the realm of gold making, leading to the popular belief that alchemists were charlatans, and the tradition itself nothing more than a fraud.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In order to protect the developing science of modern chemistry from the negative censure to which alchemy was being subjected, academic writers during the 18th-century scientific Enlightenment attempted to divorce and separate the "new" chemistry from the "old" practices of alchemy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] This move was mostly successful, and the consequences of this continued into the 19th, 20th and 21st centuries.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] During the occult revival of the early 19th century, alchemy received new attention as an occult science.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The esoteric or occultist school that arose during the 19th century held the view that the substances and operations mentioned in alchemical literature are to be interpreted in a spiritual sense, less than as a practical tradition or protoscience.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] This interpretation claimed that the obscure language of the alchemical texts, which 19th century practitioners were not always able to decipher, were an allegorical guise for spiritual, moral or mystical processes.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Two seminal figures during this period were Mary Anne Atwood and Ethan Allen Hitchcock, who independently published similar works regarding spiritual alchemy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Both rebuffed the growing successes of chemistry, developing a completely esoteric view of alchemy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Atwood wrote: "No modern art or chemistry, notwithstanding all its surreptitious claims, has any thing in common with Alchemy." Atwood's work influenced subsequent authors of the occult revival including Eliphas Levi, Arthur Edward Waite, and Rudolf Steiner.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Hitchcock, in his *Remarks Upon Alchymists* (1855) attempted to make a case for his spiritual interpretation with his claim that the alchemists wrote about a spiritual discipline under a materialistic guise in order to avoid accusations of blasphemy from the church and state.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In 1845, Baron Carl Reichenbach, published his studies on Odic force, a concept with some similarities to alchemy, but his research did not enter the mainstream of scientific discussion.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In 1946, Louis Cattiaux published the Message Retrouvé, a work that was at once philosophical, mystical and highly influenced by alchemy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In his lineage, many researchers, including Emmanuel and Charles d'Hooghvorst, are updating alchemical studies in France and Belgium.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Several women appear in the earliest history of alchemy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Michael Maier names four women who were able to make the philosophers' stone: Mary the Jewess, Cleopatra the Alchemist, Medera, and Taphnutia.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Zosimos's sister Theosebia (later known as Euthica the Arab) and Isis the Prophetess also played roles in early alchemical texts.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The first alchemist whose name we know was Mary the Jewess (c.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Early sources claim that Mary (or Maria) devised a number of improvements to alchemical equipment and tools as well as novel techniques in chemistry.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Her best known advances were in heating and distillation processes.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The laboratory water-bath, known eponymously (especially in France) as the bain-marie, is said to have been invented or at least improved by her.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Essentially a double-boiler, it was (and is) used in chemistry for processes that required gentle heating.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The tribikos (a modified distillation apparatus) and the kerotakis (a more intricate apparatus used especially for sublimations) are two other advancements in the process of distillation that are credited to her.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Although we have no writing from Mary herself, she is known from the early-fourth-century writings of Zosimos of Panopolis.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] After the Greco-Roman period, women's names appear less frequently in alchemical literature.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Towards the end of the Middle Ages and beginning of the Renaissance, due to the emergence of print, women were able to access the alchemical knowledge from texts of the preceding centuries.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Caterina Sforza, the Countess of Forlì and Lady of Imola, is one of the few confirmed female alchemists after Mary the Jewess.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] As she owned an apothecary, she would practice science and conduct experiments in her botanic gardens and laboratories.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Being knowledgeable in alchemy and pharmacology, she recorded all of her alchemical ventures in a manuscript named *Experimenti* ('Experiments').
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The manuscript contained more than four hundred recipes covering alchemy as well as cosmetics and medicine.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] One of these recipes was for the water of talc.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Talc, which makes up talcum powder, is a mineral which, when combined with water and distilled, was said to produce a solution which yielded many benefits.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] These supposed benefits included turning silver to gold and rejuvenation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] When combined with white wine, its powder form could be ingested to counteract poison.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Furthermore, if that powder was mixed and drunk with white wine, it was said to be a source of protection from any poison, sickness, or plague.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Other recipes were for making hair dyes, lotions, lip colours.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] There was also information on how to treat a variety of ailments from fevers and coughs to epilepsy and cancer.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In addition, there were instructions on producing the quintessence (or aether), an elixir which was believed to be able to heal all sicknesses, defend against diseases, and perpetuate youthfulness.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] She also wrote about creating the illustrious philosophers' stone.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Some women known for their interest in alchemy were Catherine de' Medici, the Queen of France, and Marie de' Medici, the following Queen of France, who carried out experiments in her personal laboratory.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Also, Isabella d'Este, the Marchioness of Mantua, made perfumes herself to serve as gifts.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Due to the proliferation in alchemical literature of pseudepigrapha and anonymous works, however, it is difficult to know which of the alchemists were actually women.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] This contributed to a broader pattern in which male authors credited prominent noblewomen for beauty products with the purpose of appealing to a female audience.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] For example, in *Ricettario galante* ("Gallant Recipe-Book"), the distillation of lemons and roses was attributed to Elisabetta Gonzaga, the duchess of Urbino.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the same book, Isabella d'Aragona, the daughter of Alfonso II of Naples, is accredited for recipes involving alum and mercury.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Ippolita Maria Sforza is even referred to in an anonymous manuscript about a hand lotion created with rose powder and crushed bones.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] As the sixteenth century went on, scientific culture flourished and people began collecting "secrets".
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] During this period "secrets" referred to experiments, and the most coveted ones were not those which were bizarre, but the ones which had been proven to yield the desired outcome.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In this period, the only book of secrets ascribed to a woman was *I secreti della signora Isabella Cortese* ('The Secrets of Signora Isabella Cortese').
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] This book contained information on how to turn base metals into gold, medicine, and cosmetics.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] However, it is rumoured that a man, Girolamo Ruscelli, was the real author and only used a female voice to attract female readers.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the nineteenth-century, Mary Anne Atwood's *A Suggestive Inquiry into the Hermetic Mystery* (1850) marked the return of women during the occult revival.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The history of alchemy has become a recognized subject of academic study.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] A large collection of books on alchemy is kept in the Bibliotheca Philosophica Hermetica in Amsterdam.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Journals which publish regularly on the topic of Alchemy include *Ambix*, published by the Society for the History of Alchemy and Chemistry, and *Isis*, published by the History of Science Society.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Western alchemical theory corresponds to the worldview of late antiquity in which it was born.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Concepts were imported from Neoplatonism and earlier Greek cosmology.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] As such, the classical elements appear in alchemical writings, as do the seven classical planets and the corresponding seven metals of antiquity.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Similarly, the gods of the Roman pantheon who are associated with these luminaries are discussed in alchemical literature.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The concepts of prima materia and anima mundi are central to the theory of the philosopher's stone.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The Great Work of Alchemy is often described as a series of four stages represented by colours.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Those focusing on the exoteric, such as historians of science Lawrence M.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Newman, have interpreted the *Decknamen* ('code words') of alchemy as physical substances.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] These scholars have reconstructed physicochemical experiments that they say are described in medieval and early modern texts.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] At the opposite end of the spectrum, focusing on the esoteric, scholars, such as Florin George Călian and Anna Marie Roos, who question the reading of Principe and Newman, interpret these same *Decknamen* as spiritual, religious, or psychological concepts.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] New interpretations of alchemy are still perpetuated, sometimes merging with concepts from New Age or radical environmentalism movements.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Groups like the Rosicrucians and Freemasons have a continued interest in alchemy and its symbolism.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] In the eyes of a variety of modern esoteric and neo-Hermetic practitioners, alchemy is primarily spiritual.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] In this interpretation, transmutation of lead into gold is presented as an analogy for personal transmutation, purification, and perfection.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] According to this view, early alchemists, such as Zosimos of Panopolis (c.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] 300 AD), highlighted the spiritual nature of the alchemical quest, symbolic of a religious regeneration of the human soul.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] This approach is held to have continued in the Middle Ages, as metaphysical aspects, substances, physical states, and material processes are supposed to have been used as metaphors for spiritual entities, spiritual states, and, ultimately, transformation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] In this sense, the literal meanings of alchemical formulas hid a spiritual philosophy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Applied to the alchemist, the twin goal symbolized their evolution from ignorance to enlightenment, and the stone represented a hidden spiritual truth or power that would lead to that goal.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Alchemical symbolism was important in analytical psychology.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] It was revived and popularized from near extinction by the Swiss psychologist Carl Gustav Jung.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] He observed these alchemical images occurring during the psychic process of transformation, a process that Jung called "individuation".
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Specifically, he regarded the conjuring up of images of gold or Lapis as symbolic expressions of the origin and goal of this "process of individuation".
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Together with his alchemical *mystica soror* (mystical sister), Jungian Swiss analyst Marie-Louise von Franz, Jung began collecting old alchemical texts, compiled a lexicon of key phrases with cross-references, and pored over them.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] His writings are influential in general psychology, especially for those interested in understanding the importance of dreams, symbols, and the unconscious archetypal forces (Jungian archetypes) that comprise all psychic life.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Both von Franz and Jung contributed significantly to the subject and work of alchemy and to its continued presence in psychology and contemporary culture.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Among the volumes Jung wrote on alchemy, his magnum opus is volume 14 of his *Collected Works*, *Mysterium Coniunctionis*.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Alchemy has had a long-standing relationship with art, evident in both alchemical texts and mainstream entertainment.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] *Literary alchemy* appears throughout the history of English literature from William Shakespeare to J.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Rowling, and also the popular Japanese manga *Fullmetal Alchemist*.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Here, characters or plot structure follow an alchemical magnum opus.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] In the 14th century, Chaucer began a trend of alchemical satire that can still be seen in recent fantasy works, such as those of the late Sir Terry Pratchett.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Another literary work inspired by the alchemical tradition is the 1988 novel *The Alchemist* by Brazilian writer Paulo Coelho.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Visual artists have had a similar relationship with alchemy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] While some used it as a source of satire, others worked with the alchemists themselves or integrated alchemical thought or symbols in their work.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Music was also present in the works of alchemists and continues to influence popular performers.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] In the last hundred years, alchemists have been portrayed in a magical and spagyric role in fantasy fiction, film, television, novels, comics, and video games.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] One goal of alchemy, the transmutation of base substances into gold, is now known to be impossible by means of traditional chemistry, but possible by other physical means.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Although not financially worthwhile, gold was synthesized in particle accelerators as early as 1941.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Volta drew admiration from Napoleon Bonaparte for his invention, and was invited to the Institute of France to demonstrate his invention to the members of the institute.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Throughout his life, Volta enjoyed a certain amount of closeness with the emperor who conferred upon him numerous honours.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Volta held the chair of experimental physics at the University of Pavia for nearly 40 years and was widely idolised by his students.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Despite his professional success, Volta was inclined towards domestic life and this was more apparent in his later years when he tended to live secluded from public life and more for the sake of his family.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] He died in 1827 from a series of illnesses which began in 1823.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] The SI unit of electric potential is named the volt in his honour.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Volta was born in Como, a town in northern Italy, on 18 February 1745.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] His father, Filippo Volta, was of noble lineage.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] His mother, Donna Maddalena, came from the family of the Inzaghis.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] In 1794, Volta married an aristocratic lady also from Como, Teresa Peregrini, with whom he raised three sons: Zanino, Flaminio, and Luigi.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] In 1774, he became a professor of physics at the Royal School in Como.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] A year later, he improved and popularised the electrophorus, a device that produced static electricity.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] His promotion of it was so extensive that he is often credited with its invention, even though a machine operating on the same principle was described in 1762 by the Swedish experimenter Johan Wilcke.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] In 1777, he travelled through Switzerland, where he befriended the physicist and mountaineer H.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] In the years between 1776 and 1778, Volta studied the chemistry of gases.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] He researched and discovered methane after reading a paper by Benjamin Franklin of the United States on "flammable air".
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] In November 1776, he found methane in the marshes of Angera on Lake Maggiore, and by 1778 he managed to isolate it.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] He devised experiments such as the ignition of methane by an electric spark in a closed vessel.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Volta also studied what we now call electrical capacitance, developing separate means to study both electrical potential difference (*V*) and charge (*Q*), and discovering that for a given object, they are proportional.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] This is called Volta's Law of Capacitance, and for this work, the unit of electrical potential has been named the volt.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] In 1779, he became a professor of experimental physics at the University of Pavia, a chair that he occupied for almost 40 years.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Volta's lectures were so crowded with students that the subsequent emperor Joseph II ordered the construction (based on a project by Leopold Pollack) of a new "physical theatre", today the "Aula Volta".
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Furthermore, the emperor granted Volta substantial funding to equip the physics cabinet with instruments, purchased by Volta in England and France.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] At the University History Museum of the University of Pavia there are 150 of them, used by Alessandro Volta.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Luigi Galvani, an Italian physicist, discovered something he named "animal electricity" when two different metals were connected in series with a frog's leg and to one another.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Volta realised that the frog's leg served as both a conductor of electricity (what we would now call an electrolyte) and as a detector of electricity.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] He also understood that the frog's legs were irrelevant to the electric current, which was caused by the two differing metals.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] He replaced the frog's leg with brine-soaked paper and detected the flow of electricity by other means familiar to him from his previous studies.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] This may be called Volta's Law of the electrochemical series.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] In 1800, as the result of a professional disagreement over the galvanic response advocated by Galvani, Volta invented the voltaic pile, an early electric battery, which produced a steady electric current.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Volta had determined that the most effective pair of dissimilar metals to produce electricity was zinc and copper.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Initially, he experimented with individual cells in series, each cell being a wine goblet filled with brine into which the two dissimilar electrodes were dipped.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] The voltaic pile replaced the goblets with cardboard soaked in brine.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] In announcing his invention of the voltaic pile, Volta paid tribute to the influences of William Nicholson, Tiberius Cavallo, and Abraham Bennet.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] The battery made by Volta is credited as one of the first electrochemical cells.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] It consists of two electrodes: one made of zinc, the other of copper.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] The electrolyte is either sulphuric acid mixed with water or a form of saltwater brine.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] The electrolyte exists in the form 2 H+ and SO2−4.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Zinc metal, which is higher in the electrochemical series than both copper and hydrogen, is oxidized to zinc cations (Zn2+) and creates electrons that move to the copper electrode.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] The positively charged hydrogen ions (protons) capture electrons from the copper electrode, forming bubbles of hydrogen gas, H2.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] This makes the zinc rod the negative electrode and the copper rod the positive electrode.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Thus, there are two terminals, and an electric current will flow if they are connected.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Copper metal does not react, but rather it functions as a catalyst for the hydrogen-gas formation and an electrode for the electric current.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] The sulphate anion (SO2−4) does not undergo any chemical reaction either, but migrates to the zinc anode to compensate for the charge of the zinc cations formed there.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] However, this cell also has some disadvantages.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] It is unsafe to handle, since sulphuric acid, even if diluted, can be hazardous.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Also, the power of the cell diminishes over time because the hydrogen gas is not released.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Instead, it accumulates on the surface of the copper electrode and forms a barrier between the metal and the electrolyte solution.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] In 1809, Volta became an associated member of the Royal Institute of the Netherlands.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] In honour of his work, Volta was made a count by Napoleon Bonaparte in 1810.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Volta retired in 1819 to his estate in Camnago, a *frazione* of Como, Italy, now named "Camnago Volta" in his honour.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] He died there on 5 March 1827, just after his 82nd birthday.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Volta's remains were buried in Camnago Volta.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Volta's legacy is celebrated by the Tempio Voltiano memorial located in the public gardens by the lake.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] There is also a museum that was built in his honour, which exhibits some of the equipment that Volta used to conduct experiments.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Nearby stands the Villa Olmo, which houses the Voltian Foundation, an organization promoting scientific activities.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Volta carried out his experimental studies and produced his first inventions near Como.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] In the Old Campus of the University of Pavia, there is the classroom (Aula Volta) commissioned by Emperor Joseph II to Leopoldo Pollack in 1787 for the lectures of Alessandro Volta, while in the University History Museum there are many scientific instruments that belonged to Volta.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] In 1927, an international physics conference, the Como Conference was held at Lake Como for the 100th anniversary of his death.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] His image was depicted on the Italian Lire 10,000 note (1990–1997) along with a sketch of his voltaic pile.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] In late 2017, Nvidia announced a new workstation-focused GPU microarchitecture called Volta.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] The electric eel species *Electrophorus voltai*, described in 2019 as the strongest bioelectricity producer in nature, was named after Volta.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Volta was raised as a Catholic and for all of his life continued to maintain his belief.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alessandro-volta] Because he was not ordained a clergyman as his family expected, he was sometimes accused of being irreligious and some people have speculated about his possible unbelief, stressing that "he did not join the Church", or that he virtually "ignored the church's call".
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia, either directly or indirectly, is also a building block for the synthesis of many chemicals.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In many countries, it is classified as an extremely hazardous substance.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is toxic, causing damage to cells and tissues.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] For this reason it is excreted by most animals in the urine, in the form of dissolved urea.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is produced biologically in a process called nitrogen fixation, but even more is generated industrially by the Haber process.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The process helped revolutionise agriculture by providing cheap fertilizers.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The global industrial production of ammonia in 2021 was 235 million tonnes.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Industrial ammonia is transported by road in tankers, by rail in tank wagons, by sea in gas carriers, or in cylinders.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia occurs in nature and has been detected in the interstellar medium.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia boils at −33.34 °C (−28.012 °F) at a pressure of one atmosphere, but the liquid can often be handled in the laboratory without external cooling.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Household ammonia or ammonium hydroxide is a solution of ammonia in water.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The name *ammonia* is derived from the name of the Egyptian deity *Amun* (*Ammon* in Greek) since priests and travellers of those temples would burn soils rich in ammonium chloride, which came from animal dung and urine.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Pliny, in Book XXXI of his Natural History, refers to a salt named *hammoniacum*, so called because of the proximity of its source to the Temple of Jupiter Amun (Greek Ἄμμων *Ammon*) in the Roman province of Cyrenaica.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] However, the description Pliny gives of the salt does not conform to the properties of ammonium chloride.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] According to Herbert Hoover's commentary in his English translation of Georgius Agricola's *De re metallica*, it is likely to have been common sea salt.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In any case, that salt ultimately gave ammonia and ammonium compounds their name.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Substances containing ammonia, or those that are similar to it, are called *ammoniacal*.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia arises in the atmosphere from both anthropogenic and natural sources.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The prevalent source is agriculture at around 80%.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] This includes fertilizers, urea produced by livestock, and manure in order of contribution.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Biomass burning also contributes to atmospheric ammonia, with forest fires and agricultural waste burning emitting roughly the same amount of ammonia into the atmosphere.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia can be emitted naturally from soils and plants when the concentration of ammonia in the soil or plant is higher than the concentration of ammonia in the air.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] This is known as one part of the bi-directional exchange model.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The dominant sink for atmospheric ammonia is rain.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In soil, ammonia-oxidizing archaea (AOA) and ammonia-oxidizing bacteria (AOB) convert ammonia into nitrite.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The atmospheric lifetime of ammonia through these processes vary from 12 to 48 hours.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Atmospheric ammonia gives sulfate-nitrate aerosols through reactions with sulfuric acid and nitric acid, with ammonium sulfate being prominent in this process due to its low vapour pressure.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] These aerosols affect the climate and can impact human health.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The lifetime of ammonia through oxidisation is much longer than through deposition, with it being as low as 30 days.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The amino radical then can be oxidised by multiple compounds to form greenhouse gases, such as nitrous oxide.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The oxidation of ammonia may also result in the production of nitric oxide, increasing NOx levels significantly in rural areas where relative levels are typically lower compared to urban areas.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is a colourless gas with a characteristically pungent smell.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] It is lighter than air, its density being 0.589 times that of air.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] It is easily liquefied due to the strong hydrogen bonding between molecules.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Gaseous ammonia turns to a colourless liquid, which boils at −33.1 °C (−27.58 °F), and freezes to colourless crystals at −77.7 °C (−107.86 °F).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Little data is available at very high temperatures and pressures, but the liquid-vapor critical point occurs at 405 K and 11.35 MPa.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The crystal symmetry is cubic, Pearson symbol cP16, space group P213 No.198, lattice constant 0.5125 nm.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Liquid ammonia possesses strong ionising powers reflecting its high *ε* of 22 at −35 °C (−31 °F).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In an aqueous solution, it can be expelled by boiling.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The aqueous solution of ammonia is basic, and may be described as aqueous ammonia or ammonium hydroxide.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The maximum concentration of ammonia in water (a saturated solution) has a specific gravity of 0.880 and is often known as '.880 ammonia'.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Liquid ammonia is a widely studied nonaqueous ionising solvent.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Its most conspicuous property is its ability to dissolve alkali metals to form highly coloured, electrically conductive solutions containing solvated electrons.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Apart from these remarkable solutions, much of the chemistry in liquid ammonia can be classified by analogy with related reactions in aqueous solutions.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Comparison of the physical properties of NH3 with those of water shows NH3 has the lower melting point, boiling point, density, viscosity, dielectric constant and electrical conductivity.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] These differences are attributed at least in part to the weaker hydrogen bonding in NH3.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The ionic self-dissociation constant of liquid NH3 at −50 °C is about 10−33.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Liquid ammonia is an ionising solvent, although less so than water, and dissolves a range of ionic compounds, including many nitrates, nitrites, cyanides, thiocyanates, metal cyclopentadienyl complexes and metal bis(trimethylsilyl)amides.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Most ammonium salts are soluble and act as acids in liquid ammonia solutions.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The solubility of halide salts increases from fluoride to iodide.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] A saturated solution of ammonium nitrate (**Divers' solution**, named after Edward Divers) contains 0.83 mol solute per mole of ammonia and has a vapour pressure of less than 1 bar even at 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] However, few oxyanion salts with other cations dissolve.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Liquid ammonia will dissolve all of the alkali metals and other electropositive metals such as Ca, Sr, Ba, Eu and Yb (also Mg using an electrolytic process).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] At low concentrations (<0.06 mol/L), deep blue solutions are formed: these contain metal cations and solvated electrons, free electrons that are surrounded by a cage of ammonia molecules.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] These solutions are strong reducing agents.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] At higher concentrations, the solutions are metallic in appearance and in electrical conductivity.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] At low temperatures, the two types of solution can coexist as immiscible phases.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In practice, both oxidation to dinitrogen and reduction to dihydrogen are slow, although ammonia in principle is labile under both conditions.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Although oxidation of liquid ammonia is usually slow, there is still a risk of explosion, particularly if transition metal ions are present as possible catalysts.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The stability of ammonia under reducing conditions is evidenced by the slow (hours) decomposition of solutions containing alkali metals.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The ammonia molecule has a trigonal pyramidal shape, as predicted by the valence shell electron pair repulsion theory (VSEPR theory) with an experimentally determined bond angle of 106.7°.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The central nitrogen atom has five outer electrons with an additional electron from each hydrogen atom.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] This gives a total of eight electrons, or four electron pairs that are arranged tetrahedrally.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Three of these electron pairs are used as bond pairs, which leaves one lone pair of electrons.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The lone pair repels more strongly than bond pairs; therefore, the bond angle is not 109.5°, as expected for a regular tetrahedral arrangement, but 106.7°.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] This shape gives the molecule a dipole moment and makes it polar.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The molecule's polarity, and especially its ability to form hydrogen bonds, makes ammonia highly miscible with water.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The lone pair makes ammonia a base, a proton acceptor.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is moderately basic; a 1.0 M aqueous solution has a pH of 11.6, and if a strong acid is added to such a solution until the solution is neutral (pH = 7), 99.4% of the ammonia molecules are protonated.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Temperature and salinity also affect the proportion of ammonium [NH4]+.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The latter has the shape of a regular tetrahedron and is isoelectronic with methane.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The ammonia molecule readily undergoes nitrogen inversion at room temperature; a useful analogy is an umbrella turning itself inside out in a strong wind.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The energy barrier to this inversion is 24.7 kJ/mol, and the resonance frequency is 23.79 GHz, corresponding to microwave radiation of a wavelength of 1.260 cm.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The absorption at this frequency was the first microwave spectrum to be observed and was used in the first maser.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] One of the most characteristic properties of ammonia is its basicity.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is considered to be a weak base.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] It combines with acids to form ammonium salts.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Thus, with hydrochloric acid it forms ammonium chloride, with nitric acid, ammonium nitrate, etc.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Perfectly dry ammonia gas will not combine with perfectly dry hydrogen chloride gas; moisture is necessary to bring about the reaction.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Although ammonia is well known as a weak base, it can also act as an extremely weak acid.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] It is a protic substance and is capable of formation of amides (which contain the NH−2 ion).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia often functions as a weak base, so it has some buffering ability.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Shifts in pH will cause more or fewer ammonium cations (NH+4) and amide anions (NH−2) to be present in solution.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia does not burn readily or sustain combustion, except under narrow fuel-to-air mixtures of 15–28% ammonia by volume in air.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] When mixed with oxygen, it burns with a pale yellowish-green flame.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ignition occurs when chlorine is passed into ammonia, forming nitrogen and hydrogen chloride; if chlorine is present in excess, then the highly explosive nitrogen trichloride (NCl3) is also formed.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The standard enthalpy change of combustion, Δ*H*°c, expressed per mole of ammonia and with condensation of the water formed, is −382.81 kJ/mol.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Dinitrogen is the thermodynamic product of combustion: all nitrogen oxides are unstable with respect to N2 and O2, which is the principle behind the catalytic converter.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] However, recent studies have shown that efficient and stable combustion of ammonia can be achieved using swirl combustors, thereby rekindling research interest in ammonia as a fuel for thermal power production.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The flammable range of ammonia in dry air is 15.15–27.35% and in 100% relative humidity air is 15.95–26.55%.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] For studying the kinetics of ammonia combustion, knowledge of a detailed reliable reaction mechanism is required, but this has been challenging to obtain.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is a direct or indirect precursor to most manufactured nitrogen-containing compounds.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] It is the precursor to nitric acid, which is the source for most N-substituted aromatic compounds.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Its ring-opening reaction with ethylene oxide give ethanolamine, diethanolamine, and triethanolamine.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Amides can be prepared by the reaction of ammonia with carboxylic acid and their derivatives.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] For example, ammonia reacts with formic acid (HCOOH) to yield formamide (HCONH2) when heated.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Acyl chlorides are the most reactive, but the ammonia must be present in at least a twofold excess to neutralise the hydrogen chloride formed.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Esters and anhydrides also react with ammonia to form amides.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonium salts of carboxylic acids can be dehydrated to amides by heating to 150–200 °C as long as no thermally sensitive groups are present.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Other organonitrogen compounds include alprazolam, ethanolamine, ethyl carbamate and hexamethylenetetramine.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Nitric acid is generated via the Ostwald process by oxidation of ammonia with air over a platinum catalyst at 700–850 °C (1,292–1,562 °F), ≈9 atm.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Nitric acid is used for the production of fertilisers, explosives, and many organonitrogen compounds.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The hydrogen in ammonia is susceptible to replacement by a myriad substituents.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] With alkenes and with alcohols, ammonia gives alkylamines.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] With chlorine, monochloramine is formed.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Pentavalent ammonia is known as λ5-amine, nitrogen pentahydride decomposes spontaneously into trivalent ammonia (λ3-amine) and hydrogen gas at normal conditions.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] This substance was once investigated as a possible solid rocket fuel in 1966.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is a ligand forming metal ammine complexes.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] For historical reasons, ammonia is named **ammine** in the nomenclature of coordination compounds.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] One notable ammine complex is cisplatin (Pt(NH3)2Cl2, a widely used anticancer drug.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammine complexes of chromium(III) formed the basis of Alfred Werner's revolutionary theory on the structure of coordination compounds.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Werner noted only two isomers (*fac*- and *mer*-) of the complex [CrCl3(NH3)3] could be formed, and concluded the ligands must be arranged around the metal ion at the vertices of an octahedron.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia forms 1:1 adducts with a variety of Lewis acids such as I2, phenol, and Al(CH3)3.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is a hard base (HSAB theory) and its E & C parameters are EB = 2.31 and CB = 2.04.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Its relative donor strength toward a series of acids, versus other Lewis bases, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Sulfur sticks are burnt to detect small leaks in industrial ammonia refrigeration systems.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In a laboratorial setting, gaseous ammonia can be detected by using concentrated hydrochloric acid or gaseous hydrogen chloride.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] A dense white fume (which is ammonium chloride vapour) arises from the reaction between ammonia and HCl.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The ancient Greek historian Herodotus mentioned that there were outcrops of salt in an area of Libya that was inhabited by a people called the 'Ammonians' (now the Siwa oasis in northwestern Egypt, where salt lakes still exist).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The Greek geographer Strabo also mentioned the salt from this region.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] However, the ancient authors Dioscorides, Apicius, Arrian, Synesius, and Aëtius of Amida described this salt as forming clear crystals that could be used for cooking and that were essentially rock salt.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] *Hammoniacus sal* appears in the writings of Pliny, although it is not known whether the term is equivalent to the more modern sal ammoniac (ammonium chloride).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The fermentation of urine by bacteria produces a solution of ammonia; hence fermented urine was used in Classical Antiquity to wash cloth and clothing, to remove hair from hides in preparation for tanning, to serve as a mordant in dyeing cloth, and to remove rust from iron.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] It was also used by ancient dentists to wash teeth.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In the form of sal ammoniac (نشادر, *nushadir*), ammonia was important to the Muslim alchemists.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] It was mentioned in the *Book of Stones*, likely written in the 9th century and attributed to Jābir ibn Hayyān.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] It was also important to the European alchemists of the 13th century, being mentioned by Albertus Magnus.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] It was also used by dyers in the Middle Ages in the form of fermented urine to alter the colour of vegetable dyes.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In the 15th century, Basilius Valentinus showed that ammonia could be obtained by the action of alkalis on sal ammoniac.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] At a later period, when sal ammoniac was obtained by distilling the hooves and horns of oxen and neutralising the resulting carbonate with hydrochloric acid, the name 'spirit of hartshorn' was applied to ammonia.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Gaseous ammonia was first isolated by Joseph Black in 1756 by reacting *sal ammoniac* (ammonium chloride) with *calcined magnesia* (magnesium oxide).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] It was isolated again by Peter Woulfe in 1767, by Carl Wilhelm Scheele in 1770 and by Joseph Priestley in 1773 and was termed by him 'alkaline air'.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Eleven years later in 1785, Claude Louis Berthollet ascertained its composition.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The production of ammonia from nitrogen in the air (and hydrogen) was invented by Fritz Haber and Robert LeRossignol.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Later, Carl Bosch developed the industrial method for ammonia production (Haber–Bosch process).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] It was first used on an industrial scale in Germany during World War I, following the allied blockade that cut off the supply of nitrates from Chile.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The ammonia was used to produce explosives to sustain war efforts.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The Nobel Prize in Chemistry 1918 was awarded to Fritz Haber "for the synthesis of ammonia from its elements".
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Before the availability of natural gas, hydrogen as a precursor to ammonia production was produced via the electrolysis of water or using the chloralkali process.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] With the advent of the steel industry in the 20th century, ammonia became a byproduct of the production of coking coal.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In the US as of 2019, approximately 88% of ammonia was used as fertilisers either as its salts, solutions or anhydrously.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] When applied to soil, it helps provide increased yields of crops such as maize and wheat.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] 30% of agricultural nitrogen applied in the US is in the form of anhydrous ammonia, and worldwide, 110 million tonnes are applied each year.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Solutions of ammonia ranging from 16% to 25% are used in the fermentation industry as a source of nitrogen for microorganisms and to adjust pH during fermentation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] African countries aim to use their potential to produce renewable ammonia to reduce their dependence on fertiliser imports.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Because of ammonia's vapourisation properties, it is a useful refrigerant.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] It was commonly used before the popularisation of chlorofluorocarbons (Freons).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Anhydrous ammonia is widely used in industrial refrigeration applications and hockey rinks because of its high energy efficiency and low cost.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] It suffers from the disadvantage of toxicity, and requiring corrosion resistant components, which restricts its domestic and small-scale use.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Along with its use in modern vapour-compression refrigeration it is used in a mixture along with hydrogen and water in absorption refrigerators.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The Kalina cycle, which is of growing importance to geothermal power plants, depends on the wide boiling range of the ammonia–water mixture.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia coolant is also used in the radiators aboard the International Space Station in loops that are used to regulate the internal temperature and enable temperature-dependent experiments.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The ammonia is under sufficient pressure to remain liquid throughout the process.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Single-phase ammonia cooling systems also serve the power electronics in each pair of solar arrays.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The potential importance of ammonia as a refrigerant has increased with the discovery that vented CFCs and HFCs are potent and stable greenhouse gases.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] As early as in 1895, it was known that ammonia was 'strongly antiseptic; it requires 1.4 grams per litre to preserve beef tea (broth).' In one study, anhydrous ammonia destroyed 99.999% of zoonotic bacteria in three types of animal feed, but not silage.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Anhydrous ammonia is currently used commercially to reduce or eliminate microbial contamination of beef.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Lean finely textured beef (popularly known as 'pink slime') in the beef industry is made from fatty beef trimmings (c.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] 50–70% fat) by removing the fat using heat and centrifugation, then treating it with ammonia to kill *E. coli*.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The process was deemed effective and safe by the US Department of Agriculture based on a study that found that the treatment reduces *E. coli* to undetectable levels.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] There have been safety concerns about the process as well as consumer complaints about the taste and smell of ammonia-treated beef.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia has been used as fuel, and is a proposed alternative to fossil fuels and hydrogen, especially in maritime transport.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Being liquid at ambient temperature under its own vapour pressure and having high volumetric and gravimetric energy density, ammonia is considered a suitable carrier for hydrogen, and may be cheaper than direct transport of liquid hydrogen.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Compared to hydrogen, ammonia is easier to store.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Compared to hydrogen as a fuel, ammonia is much more energy efficient, and could be produced, stored and delivered at a much lower cost than hydrogen, which must be kept compressed or as a cryogenic liquid.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The raw energy density of liquid ammonia is 11.5 MJ/L, which is about a third that of diesel.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia can also be converted back to hydrogen to be used to power hydrogen fuel cells, or it may be used directly within high-temperature solid oxide direct ammonia fuel cells to provide efficient power sources that do not emit greenhouse gases.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia to hydrogen conversion can be achieved through the sodium amide process or the catalytic decomposition of ammonia using solid catalysts.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia production currently creates 1.8% of global CO2 emissions.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] 'Green ammonia' is ammonia produced by using green hydrogen (hydrogen produced by electrolysis with electricity from renewable energy), whereas 'blue ammonia' is ammonia produced using blue hydrogen (hydrogen produced by steam methane reforming) where the carbon dioxide has been captured and stored.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In a world first in 2020, Saudi Arabia shipped 40 metric tons of liquid 'blue ammonia' to Japan for use as a fuel.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] It was produced as a by-product by petrochemical industries, and can be burned without giving off greenhouse gases.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Its energy density by volume is nearly double that of liquid hydrogen.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] If the process of creating it can be scaled up via purely renewable resources, producing green ammonia, it could make a major difference in avoiding climate change.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Green ammonia is considered as a potential fuel for new ships, including future container ships.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is expected to increase in usage as a fuel source for shipping The IEA forecasts that ammonia will meet approximately 45% of shipping fuel demands by 2050.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In 2020, the companies DSME and MAN Energy Solutions announced the construction of an ammonia-based ship, DSME plans to commercialise it by 2025.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The use of ammonia as a potential alternative fuel for aircraft jet engines is also being explored.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In addition, hybrid engine configurations for supersonic aviation employing ammonia fuel have been investigated.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Japan is implementing a plan to develop ammonia co-firing technology that can increase the use of ammonia in power generation, as part of efforts to assist domestic and other Asian utilities to accelerate their transition to carbon neutrality.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In October 2021, the first International Conference on Fuel Ammonia (ICFA2021) was held.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In June 2022, IHI Corporation succeeded in reducing greenhouse gases by over 99% during combustion of liquid ammonia in a 2,000-kilowatt-class gas turbine achieving truly CO2-free power generation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In July 2022, Quad nations of Japan, the US, Australia and India agreed to promote technological development for clean-burning hydrogen and ammonia as fuels at the security grouping's first energy meeting.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] As of 2022, however, significant amounts of NO*x* are produced.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Nitrous oxide may also be a problem as it is a "*greenhouse gas that is known to possess up to 300 times the Global Warming Potential (GWP) of carbon dioxide*".
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia engines or ammonia motors, using ammonia as a working fluid, have been proposed and occasionally used.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The principle is similar to that used in a fireless locomotive, but with ammonia as the working fluid, instead of steam or compressed air.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia engines were used experimentally in the 19th century by Goldsworthy Gurney in the UK and the St.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Charles Streetcar Line in New Orleans in the 1870s and 1880s, and during World War II ammonia was used to power buses in Belgium.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is sometimes proposed as a practical alternative to fossil fuel for internal combustion engines.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] However, ammonia cannot be easily used in existing Otto cycle engines because of its very narrow flammability range.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Despite this, several tests have been run.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Its high octane rating of 120 and low flame temperature allows the use of high compression ratios without a penalty of high NO*x* production.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Since ammonia contains no carbon, its combustion cannot produce carbon dioxide, carbon monoxide, hydrocarbons, or soot.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] At high temperature and in the presence of a suitable catalyst, ammonia decomposes into its constituent elements.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Decomposition of ammonia is a slightly endothermic process requiring 23 kJ/mol (5.5 kcal/mol) of ammonia, and yields hydrogen and nitrogen gas.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Rocket engines have also been fuelled by ammonia.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The Reaction Motors XLR99 rocket engine that powered the X-15 hypersonic research aircraft used liquid ammonia.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Although not as powerful as other fuels, it left no soot in the reusable rocket engine, and its density approximately matches the density of the oxidiser, liquid oxygen, which simplified the aircraft's design.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Liquid ammonia is also an attractive alternative to liquid hydrogen as a nuclear-thermal rocket propellant, offering increased thrust (at reduced fuel efficiency).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The company ACWA Power and the city of Neom have announced the construction of a green hydrogen and ammonia plant in 2020.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is used to scrub SO2 from the burning of fossil fuels, and the resulting product is converted to ammonium sulfate for use as fertiliser.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia neutralises the nitrogen oxide (NO*x*) pollutants emitted by diesel engines.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] This technology, called SCR (selective catalytic reduction), relies on a vanadia-based catalyst.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia may be used to mitigate gaseous spills of phosgene.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia, as the vapour released by smelling salts, has found significant use as a respiratory stimulant.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is commonly used in the illegal manufacture of methamphetamine through a Birch reduction.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The Birch method of making methamphetamine is dangerous because the alkali metal and liquid ammonia are both extremely reactive, and the temperature of liquid ammonia makes it susceptible to explosive boiling when reactants are added.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Liquid ammonia is used for treatment of cotton materials, giving properties like mercerisation, using alkalis.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In particular, it is used for prewashing of wool.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] At standard temperature and pressure, ammonia is less dense than atmosphere and has approximately 45–48% of the lifting power of hydrogen or helium.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia has sometimes been used to fill balloons as a lifting gas.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Because of its relatively high boiling point (compared to helium and hydrogen), ammonia could potentially be refrigerated and liquefied aboard an airship to reduce lift and add ballast (and returned to a gas to add lift and reduce ballast).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia has been used to darken quartersawn white oak in Arts & Crafts and Mission-style furniture.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia fumes react with the natural tannins in the wood and cause it to change colour.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is used as an ingredient in various cleaning products, such as Windex (until 2006), in the form of ammonia solution.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The US Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) has set a 15-minute exposure limit for gaseous ammonia of 35 ppm by volume in the environmental air and an 8-hour exposure limit of 25 ppm by volume.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Other organisations have varying exposure levels.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] US Navy Standards [US Bureau of Ships 1962] maximum allowable concentrations (MACs): for continuous exposure (60 days) is 25 ppm; for exposure of 1 hour is 400 ppm.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is an irritant and irritation increases with concentration; the permissible exposure limit is 25 ppm, and lethal above 500 ppm by volume.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia vapour has a sharp, irritating, pungent odour that acts as a warning of potentially dangerous exposure.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The average odour threshold is 5 ppm, well below any danger or damage.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Exposure to very high concentrations of gaseous ammonia can result in lung damage and death.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is regulated in the US as a non-flammable gas, but it meets the definition of a material that is toxic by inhalation and requires a hazardous safety permit when transported in quantities greater than 3,500 US gallons (13,000 L; 2,900 imp gal).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The toxicity of ammonia solutions does not usually cause problems for humans and other mammals because they possess metabolic pathways that prevent ammonia from accumulating in the bloodstream.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is converted to carbamoyl phosphate by the enzyme carbamoyl phosphate synthetase and then enters the urea cycle, where it is incorporated into amino acids or excreted as urea.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Fish and amphibians lack this internal detoxification mechanism because they normally eliminate ammonia directly into the surrounding water.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] As a result, they are highly sensitive to elevated environmental concentrations: even dilute levels in the water can impede excretion and lead to toxic accumulation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] For this reason, ammonia in aquatic environments is classified as *dangerous for the environment*.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Atmospheric ammonia also plays a key role in the formation of fine particulate matter.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is also a constituent of tobacco smoke.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is present in coking wastewater streams, as a liquid by-product of the production of coke from coal.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In some cases, the ammonia is discharged to the marine environment where it acts as a pollutant.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The Whyalla Steelworks in South Australia is one example of a coke-producing facility that discharges ammonia into marine waters.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia toxicity is believed to be a cause of otherwise unexplained losses in fish hatcheries.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Excess ammonia may accumulate and cause alteration of metabolism or increases in the body pH of the exposed organism.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] At lower concentrations, around 0.05 mg/L, un-ionised ammonia is harmful to fish species and can result in poor growth and feed conversion rates, reduced fecundity and fertility and increase stress and susceptibility to bacterial infections and diseases.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Exposed to excess ammonia, fish may suffer loss of equilibrium, hyper-excitability, increased respiratory activity and oxygen uptake and increased heart rate.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] At concentrations exceeding 2.0 mg/L, ammonia causes gill and tissue damage, extreme lethargy, convulsions, coma, and death.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Experiments have shown that the lethal concentration for a variety of fish species ranges from 0.2 to 2.0 mg/L.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] During winter, when reduced feeds are administered to aquaculture stock, ammonia levels can be higher.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Lower ambient temperatures reduce the rate of algal photosynthesis so less ammonia is removed by any algae present.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Within an aquaculture environment, especially at large scale, there is no fast-acting remedy to elevated ammonia levels.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Prevention rather than correction is recommended to reduce harm to farmed fish and in open water systems, the surrounding environment.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Similar to propane, anhydrous ammonia boils below room temperature when at atmospheric pressure.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] A storage vessel capable of 250 psi (1.7 MPa) is suitable to contain the liquid.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia is used in numerous different industrial applications requiring carbon or stainless steel storage vessels.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia with at least 0.2% by weight water content is not corrosive to carbon steel.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] NH3 carbon steel construction storage tanks with 0.2% by weight or more of water could last more than 50 years in service.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Experts warn that ammonium compounds not be allowed to come in contact with bases (unless in an intended and contained reaction), as dangerous quantities of ammonia gas could be released.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The hazards of ammonia solutions depend on the concentration: 'dilute' ammonia solutions are usually 5–10% by weight (< 5.62 mol/L); 'concentrated' solutions are usually prepared at >25% by weight.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] A 25% (by weight) solution has a density of 0.907 g/cm3, and a solution that has a lower density will be more concentrated.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The European Union classification of ammonia solutions is given in the table.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The ammonia vapour from concentrated ammonia solutions is severely irritating to the eyes and the respiratory tract, and experts warn that these solutions only be handled in a fume hood.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Saturated ('0.880'–see *§ Properties*) solutions can develop a significant pressure inside a closed bottle in warm weather, and experts also warn that the bottle be opened with care.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] This is not usually a problem for 25% ('0.900') solutions.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Experts warn that ammonia solutions not be mixed with halogens, as toxic and/or explosive products are formed.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Anhydrous ammonia is classified as toxic (**T**) and dangerous for the environment (**N**).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The gas is flammable (autoignition temperature: 651 °C) and can form explosive mixtures with air (16–25%).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The permissible exposure limit (PEL) in the United States is 50 ppm (35 mg/m3), while the IDLH concentration is estimated at 300 ppm.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Repeated exposure to ammonia lowers the sensitivity to the smell of the gas: normally the odour is detectable at concentrations of less than 50 ppm, but desensitised individuals may not detect it even at concentrations of 100 ppm.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Anhydrous ammonia corrodes copper- and zinc-containing alloys, which makes brass fittings not appropriate for handling the gas.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Liquid ammonia can also attack rubber and certain plastics.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia reacts violently with the halogens.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Nitrogen triiodide, a primary high explosive, is formed when ammonia comes in contact with iodine.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia causes the explosive polymerisation of ethylene oxide.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] It also forms explosive fulminating compounds with compounds of gold, silver, mercury, germanium or tellurium, and with stibine.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Violent reactions have also been reported with acetaldehyde, hypochlorite solutions, potassium ferricyanide and peroxides.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Ammonia has one of the highest rates of production of any inorganic chemical.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Production is sometimes expressed in terms of "fixed nitrogen".
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Global production was estimated as being 160 million tonnes in 2020 (147 tons of fixed nitrogen).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] China accounted for 26.5% of that, followed by Russia at 11.0%, the United States at 9.5%, and India at 8.3%.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The Haber process, also called the Haber–Bosch process, is the main industrial procedure for the production of ammonia.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] This reaction is exothermic but disfavored in terms of entropy because four equivalents of reactant gases are converted into two equivalents of product gas.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] However, due to the extremely high kinetic barriers to bond cleavage, high pressures and temperatures are needed to drive the reaction forward.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The Haber Process was first created by the German Chemist Fritz Haber, then developed after a few years by Carl Bosch.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The German chemists Fritz Haber and Carl Bosch developed the process in the first decade of the 20th century, and its improved efficiency over existing methods such as the Birkeland–Eyde and Frank–Caro processes was a major advancement in the industrial production of ammonia.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The Haber process can be combined with steam reforming to produce ammonia with just three chemical inputs: water, natural gas, and atmospheric nitrogen.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Both Haber and Bosch were eventually awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry: Haber in 1918 for ammonia synthesis specifically, and Bosch in 1931 for related contributions to high-pressure chemistry.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The electrochemical synthesis of ammonia involves the reductive formation of lithium nitride, which can be protonated to ammonia, given a proton source.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The first use of this chemistry was reported in 1930, where lithium solutions in ethanol were used to produce ammonia at pressures of up to 1000 bar, with ethanol acting as the proton source.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Beyond simply mediating proton transfer to the nitrogen reduction reaction, ethanol has been found to play a multifaceted role, influencing electrolyte transformations and contributing to the formation of the solid electrolyte interphase, which enhances overall reaction efficiency.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In 1994, Tsuneto et al. used lithium electrodeposition in tetrahydrofuran to synthesize ammonia at more moderate pressures with reasonable Faradaic efficiency.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Subsequent studies have further explored the ethanol–tetrahydrofuran system for electrochemical ammonia synthesis.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In 2020, a solvent-agnostic gas diffusion electrode was shown to improve nitrogen transport to the reactive lithium.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] NH3 production rates of up to 30 ± 5 nmol/(s⋅cm2) and Faradaic efficiencies of up to 47.5 ± 4% at ambient temperature and 1 bar pressure were achieved.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In 2021, it was demonstrated that ethanol could be replaced with a tetraalkyl phosphonium salt.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The study observed NH3 production rates of 53 ± 1 nmol/(s⋅cm2) at 69 ± 1% Faradaic efficiency experiments under 0.5 bar hydrogen and 19.5 bar nitrogen partial pressure at ambient temperature.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] Technology based on this electrochemistry is being developed for commercial fertiliser and fuel production.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] In 2022, ammonia was produced via the lithium mediated process in a continuous-flow electrolyzer also demonstrating the hydrogen gas as proton source.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p01] The study synthesised ammonia at 61 ± 1% Faradaic efficiency at a current density of −6 mA/cm2 at 1 bar and room temperature.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] For example, it is required for the formation of amino acids and nucleic acids, fundamental building blocks of life.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Within a cell, glutamate serves this role.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] In the bloodstream, glutamine is a source of ammonia.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Ammonia is both a metabolic waste and a metabolic input throughout the biosphere.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] It is an important source of nitrogen for living systems.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Although atmospheric nitrogen abounds (more than 75%), few living creatures are capable of using atmospheric nitrogen in its diatomic form, N2 gas.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Therefore, nitrogen fixation is required for the synthesis of amino acids, which are the building blocks of protein.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Some plants rely on ammonia and other nitrogenous wastes incorporated into the soil by decaying matter.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Others, such as nitrogen-fixing legumes, benefit from symbiotic relationships with rhizobia bacteria that create ammonia from atmospheric nitrogen.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] In humans, inhaling ammonia in high concentrations can be fatal.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Exposure to ammonia can cause headaches, edema, impaired memory, seizures and coma as it is neurotoxic in nature.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] In certain organisms, ammonia is produced from atmospheric nitrogen by enzymes called nitrogenases.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The overall process is called nitrogen fixation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Intense effort has been directed toward understanding the mechanism of biological nitrogen fixation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The scientific interest in this problem is motivated by the unusual structure of the active site of the enzyme, which consists of an Fe7MoS9 ensemble.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Ammonia is also a metabolic product of amino acid deamination catalysed by enzymes such as glutamate dehydrogenase 1.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Ammonia excretion is common in aquatic animals.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] In humans, it is quickly converted to urea (by liver), which is much less toxic, particularly less basic.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] This urea is a major component of the dry weight of urine.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Most reptiles, birds, insects, and snails excrete uric acid solely as nitrogenous waste.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Ammonia plays a role in both normal and abnormal animal physiology.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] It is biosynthesised through normal amino acid metabolism and is toxic in high concentrations.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The liver converts ammonia to urea through a series of reactions known as the urea cycle.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Liver dysfunction, such as that seen in cirrhosis, may lead to elevated amounts of ammonia in the blood (hyperammonemia).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Likewise, defects in the enzymes responsible for the urea cycle, such as ornithine transcarbamylase, lead to hyperammonemia.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Hyperammonemia contributes to the confusion and coma of hepatic encephalopathy, as well as the neurological disease common in people with urea cycle defects and organic acidurias.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Ammonia is important for normal animal acid/base balance.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] After formation of ammonium from glutamine, α-ketoglutarate may be degraded to produce two bicarbonate ions, which are then available as buffers for dietary acids.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Ammonium is excreted in the urine, resulting in net acid loss.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Ammonia may itself diffuse across the renal tubules, combine with a hydrogen ion, and thus allow for further acid excretion.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Ammonium ions are a toxic waste product of metabolism in animals.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] In fish and aquatic invertebrates, it is excreted directly into the water.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] In mammals, sharks, and amphibians, it is converted in the urea cycle to urea, which is less toxic and can be stored more efficiently.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] In birds, reptiles, and terrestrial snails, metabolic ammonium is converted into uric acid, which is solid and can therefore be excreted with minimal water loss.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Ammonia has been detected in the atmospheres of the giant planets Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus and Neptune, along with other gases such as methane, hydrogen, and helium.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The interior of Saturn may include frozen ammonia crystals.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Ammonia was first detected in interstellar space in 1968, based on microwave emissions from the direction of the galactic core.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] This was the first polyatomic molecule to be so detected.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The sensitivity of the molecule to a broad range of excitations and the ease with which it can be observed in a number of regions has made ammonia one of the most important molecules for studies of molecular clouds.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The relative intensity of the ammonia lines can be used to measure the temperature of the emitting medium.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The following isotopic species of ammonia have been detected: NH3,15NH3, NH2D, NHD2, and ND3.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The detection of triply deuterated ammonia was considered a surprise as deuterium is relatively scarce.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] It is thought that the low-temperature conditions allow this molecule to survive and accumulate.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Since its interstellar discovery, NH3 has proved to be an invaluable spectroscopic tool in the study of the interstellar medium.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] With a large number of transitions sensitive to a wide range of excitation conditions, NH3 has been widely astronomically detected–its detection has been reported in hundreds of journal articles.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Listed below is a sample of journal articles that highlights the range of detectors that have been used to identify ammonia.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The study of interstellar ammonia has been important to a number of areas of research in the last few decades.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Some of these are delineated below and primarily involve using ammonia as an interstellar thermometer.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The interstellar abundance for ammonia has been measured for a variety of environments.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The [NH3]/[H2] ratio has been estimated to range from 10−7 in small dark clouds up to 10−5 in the dense core of the Orion molecular cloud complex.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The rate constant, *k*, of this reaction depends on the temperature of the environment, with a value of $5.2\times 10^{-6}$ at 10 K.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The rate constant was calculated from the formula ⁠ $k=a(T/300)^{B}$ ⁠.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Assuming an NH+4 abundance of $3\times 10^{-7}$ and an electron abundance of 10−7 typical of molecular clouds, the formation will proceed at a rate of 1.6×10−9 cm−3s−1 in a molecular cloud of total density 105 cm−3.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] All other proposed formation reactions have rate constants of between two and 13 orders of magnitude smaller, making their contribution to the abundance of ammonia relatively insignificant.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Assuming H2 densities of 105 and [NH2]/[H2] ratio of 10−7, this reaction proceeds at a rate of 2.2×10−12, more than three orders of magnitude slower than the primary reaction above.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] There are 113 total proposed reactions leading to the destruction of NH3.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Of these, 39 were tabulated in extensive tables of the chemistry among C, N and O compounds.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] These calculations assumed the given rate constants and abundances of [NH3]/[H2] = 10−5, [[H3]+]/[H2] = 2×10−5, [HCO+]/[H2] = 2×10−9, and total densities of *n* = 105, typical of cold, dense, molecular clouds.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Clearly, between these two primary reactions, equation (**1**) is the dominant destruction reaction, with a rate ≈10,000 times faster than equation (**2**).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] This is due to the relatively high abundance of [H3]+.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Radio observations of NH3 from the Effelsberg 100-m Radio Telescope reveal that the ammonia line is separated into two components–a background ridge and an unresolved core.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The background corresponds well with the locations previously detected CO.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The 25 m Chilbolton telescope in England detected radio signatures of ammonia in H II regions, HNH2O masers, H–H objects, and other objects associated with star formation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] A comparison of emission line widths indicates that turbulent or systematic velocities do not increase in the central cores of molecular clouds.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Microwave radiation from ammonia was observed in several galactic objects including W3(OH), Orion A, W43, W51, and five sources in the galactic centre.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The high detection rate indicates that this is a common molecule in the interstellar medium and that high-density regions are common in the galaxy.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] VLA observations of NH3 in seven regions with high-velocity gaseous outflows revealed condensations of less than 0.1 pc in L1551, S140, and Cepheus A.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Three individual condensations were detected in Cepheus A, one of them with a highly elongated shape.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] They may play an important role in creating the bipolar outflow in the region.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Extragalactic ammonia was imaged using the VLA in IC 342.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The hot gas has temperatures above 70 K, which was inferred from ammonia line ratios and appears to be closely associated with the innermost portions of the nuclear bar seen in CO.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Based upon temperature and density diagnostics, it is concluded that in general such clumps are probably the sites of massive star formation in an early evolutionary phase prior to the development of an ultracompact HII region.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Absorption at 2.97 micrometres due to solid ammonia was recorded from interstellar grains in the Becklin–Neugebauer Object and probably in NGC 2264-IR as well.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] This detection helped explain the physical shape of previously poorly understood and related ice absorption lines.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] A spectrum of the disk of Jupiter was obtained from the Kuiper Airborne Observatory, covering the 100 to 300 cm−1 spectral range.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Analysis of the spectrum provides information on global mean properties of ammonia gas and an ammonia ice haze.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] A total of 149 dark cloud positions were surveyed for evidence of 'dense cores' by using the (J,K) = (1,1) rotating inversion line of NH3.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] In general, the cores are not spherically shaped, with aspect ratios ranging from 1.1 to 4.4.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] It is also found that cores with stars have broader lines than cores without stars.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Ammonia has been detected in the Draco Nebula and in one or possibly two molecular clouds, which are associated with the high-latitude galactic infrared cirrus.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The finding is significant because they may represent the birthplaces for the Population I metallicity B-type stars in the galactic halo that could have been borne in the galactic disk.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] By balancing and stimulated emission with spontaneous emission, it is possible to construct a relation between excitation temperature and density.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Moreover, since the transitional levels of ammonia can be approximated by a 2-level system at low temperatures, this calculation is fairly simple.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] This premise can be applied to dark clouds, regions suspected of having extremely low temperatures and possible sites for future star formation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Detections of ammonia in dark clouds show very narrow lines – indicative not only of low temperatures, but also of a low level of inner-cloud turbulence.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Line ratio calculations provide a measurement of cloud temperature that is independent of previous CO observations.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The ammonia observations were consistent with CO measurements of rotation temperatures of ≈10 K.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] With this, densities can be determined, and have been calculated to range between 104 and 105 cm−3 in dark clouds.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Mapping of NH3 gives typical clouds sizes of 0.1 pc and masses near 1 solar mass.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] These cold, dense cores are the sites of future star formation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Ultra-compact HII regions are among the best tracers of high-mass star formation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] The dense material surrounding UCHII regions is likely primarily molecular.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Since a complete study of massive star formation necessarily involves the cloud from which the star formed, ammonia is an invaluable tool in understanding this surrounding molecular material.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Since this molecular material can be spatially resolved, it is possible to constrain the heating/ionising sources, temperatures, masses, and sizes of the regions.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Doppler-shifted velocity components allow for the separation of distinct regions of molecular gas that can trace outflows and hot cores originating from forming stars.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Ammonia has been detected in external galaxies, and by simultaneously measuring several lines, it is possible to directly measure the gas temperature in these galaxies.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] Line ratios imply that gas temperatures are warm (≈50 K), originating from dense clouds with sizes of tens of parsecs.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/alkaline-air-p02] This picture is consistent with the picture within our Milky Way galaxy – hot dense molecular cores form around newly forming stars embedded in larger clouds of molecular material on the scale of several hundred parsecs (giant molecular clouds; GMCs).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride is a salt that crystallizes in a motif akin those for the alkali metal chlorides.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] At least three phases have been characterized.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] According to X-ray crystallography, these phases include ordered and disordered variants of the sodium chloride and cesium chloride structures.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] In the NaCl structure, which is found at room temperature and 1 atmosphere, tetrahedral ammonium cations hydrogen bond to four of the eight chloride anions that encase the cation.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride melts reversibly in a normal way near 500 °C but only under pressure.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] When dissolved, the lattice disassembles into separate chloride and ammonium cations.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] At neutral pH, the N-H bonds rapidly exchange with water.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Not only is that method the principal one for the manufacture of ammonium chloride, but also it is used to minimize ammonia release in some industrial operations.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride occurs naturally in volcanic regions, appearing as a sublimate on rocks near fume-releasing vents (fumaroles).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] The crystals deposit directly from the gaseous state and tend to be short-lived, as they dissolve easily in water.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] A solution of 5% by mass of ammonium chloride in water has a pH in the range 4.6 to 6.0.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] The dominant application of ammonium chloride is as a nitrogen source in fertilizers (corresponding to 90% of the world production of ammonium chloride) such as chloroammonium phosphate.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] The main crops fertilized this way are rice and wheat in Asia.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] When using ammonium chloride as a nitrogen fertilizer for plants, the appropriate concentration is applied to provide sufficient nutrients without causing harm.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride is approximately 26% nitrogen by weight and can be used to supply nitrogen to plants, especially those preferring slightly acidic conditions.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] The concentration for nitrogen fertilization in solution is between 50 and 100 milligrams of nitrogen per liter of water (mg N/L), which is equivalent to 50–100 parts per million (ppm) nitrogen, which translates to approximately 0.2 to 0.4 grams of ammonium chloride per liter of water.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride can acidify the soil over time, so soil pH is regularly monitored, especially when growing plants sensitive to acidic conditions.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Some plants are sensitive to chloride ions (e.g., avocados, beans, grapes), so applying ammonium chloride to such plants should be done with extra caution to prevent chloride toxicity.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] While ammonium chloride can be beneficial as a nitrogen source, improper use can harm plants and the environment.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Over time, water can evaporate from the solution, especially if not stored in a tightly sealed container, which increases the concentration of ammonium chloride, and may lead to over-fertilization and potential damage to plants when applied.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] While ammonium chloride is relatively stable, prolonged storage may lead to minor changes in pH due to ongoing hydrolysis, especially if the solution is exposed to air, potentially impacting plants sensitive to acidity of the soil.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] If the water used is not distilled or deionized, dissolved minerals and impurities may precipitate over time, altering the nutrient balance of the solution.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride was used in pyrotechnics in the 18th century but was superseded by safer and less hygroscopic chemicals.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Its purpose was to provide a chlorine donor to enhance the green and blue colours from copper ions in the flame.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] It had a secondary use to provide white smoke, but its ready double decomposition reaction with potassium chlorate producing the highly unstable ammonium chlorate made its use very dangerous.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride is used as a flux in preparing metals to be tin coated, galvanized or soldered.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] It works as a flux by cleaning the surface of workpieces by reacting with the metal oxides at the surface to form a volatile metal chloride.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] For that purpose, it is sold in blocks at hardware stores for use in cleaning the tip of a soldering iron, and it can also be included in solder as flux.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride is used as an expectorant in cough medicine.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Its expectorant action is caused by irritative action on the bronchial mucosa, which causes the production of excess respiratory tract fluid, which presumably is easier to cough up.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium salts are an irritant to the gastric mucosa and may induce nausea and vomiting.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride is used as a systemic acidifying agent in treatment of severe metabolic alkalosis, in oral acid loading test to diagnose distal renal tubular acidosis, to maintain the urine at an acid pH in the treatment of some urinary-tract disorders.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride, under the name *sal ammoniac* or *salmiak* is used as food additive under the E number E510, working as a yeast nutrient in breadmaking and as an acidifier.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] It is a feed supplement for cattle and an ingredient in nutritive media for yeasts and many microorganisms.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride is used in baking to give cookies a very crisp texture, to spice up dark sweets called salty liquorice (popular in the Nordic countries, Benelux and northern Germany), and in the liquor Salmiakki Koskenkorva for flavouring.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] In Turkey, Iran, Tajikistan, India, Pakistan and Arab countries it is called "noshader" and is used to improve the crispness of snacks such as *samosas* and *jalebi*.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride has been used historically to produce low temperatures in cooling baths.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride solutions with ammonia are used as buffer solutions including ACK (Ammonium-Chloride-Potassium) lysis buffer.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] The same technique is applied in archaeology to eliminate reflection on glass and similar specimens for photography.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] In organic synthesis saturated NH4Cl solution is typically used to quench reaction mixtures.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] It has a lambda transition at 242.8 K and zero pressure.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Giant squid and some other large squid species maintain neutral buoyancy in seawater through an ammonium chloride solution which is found throughout their bodies and is less dense than seawater.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] This differs from the method of flotation used by most fish, which involves a gas-filled swim bladder.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Around the turn of the 20th century, ammonium chloride was used in aqueous solution as the electrolyte in Leclanché cells that found a commercial use as the "local battery" in subscribers' telephone installations.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Those cells later evolved into zinc–carbon batteries still using ammonium chloride as electrolyte.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride is known to be an aggressive cleaning agent.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] A penetrating and intense reddish brown color is stained into concrete surfaces with a mixture of ammonium chloride and ferric chloride.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride can also be used in the process of making albumen silver prints, commonly known as albumen prints.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] In traditional photographic printing processes of the 19th century, ammonium chloride served as a key component in preparing the albumen solution used to coat the photographic paper.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Albumen printing was the dominant photographic printing technique from the 1850s through the 1890s, prized for its fine detail and rich tonal rendition.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] The incorporation of ammonium chloride in the albumen solution was a significant factor in the quality and popularity of this photographic process.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] The process involves mixing egg whites (albumen) with ammonium chloride to create a viscous solution.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] This mixture is then applied as a thin layer onto paper, which, after drying, forms a smooth and glossy surface.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride acts as a salting agent, contributing chloride ions that are essential for forming light-sensitive silver chloride when the coated paper is subsequently sensitized with a solution of silver nitrate.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Upon exposure to light, the silver chloride reduces to metallic silver, creating a visible image.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] The use of ammonium chloride, as opposed to sodium chloride (common salt), can influence the contrast and tonal range of the final print, often yielding warmer tones and greater image clarity.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride is used in a ~5% aqueous solution to work on oil wells with clay swelling problems.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Other uses include in hair shampoo, in the glue that bonds plywood, and in cleaning products.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] In hair shampoo, it is used as a thickening agent in ammonium-based surfactant systems such as ammonium lauryl sulfate.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Ammonium chloride is used in the textile and leather industry, in dyeing, tanning, textile printing and cotton clustering.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] In woodworking, a solution of ammonium chloride and water, when applied to unfinished wood, will burn when subjected to a heat gun resulting in a branding iron mark without use of a branding iron.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] The solution can be painted onto the wood or applied with a common rubber stamp.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] It was in deposits near the temple of Ammon in Siwa that the Romans extracted ammonium chloride, which they called *sal ammoniacus* (Ammonian Salt) in honor of the Siwan Berber god Ammon.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] *Sal ammoniacus* is itself borrowed from the ancient Greek *ammoniakos*, which meant 'relating to Ammon'.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Pliny, in Book XXXI of his *Natural History*, refers to a salt produced in the Roman province of Cyrenaica named *hammoniacum*, so called because of its proximity to the nearby Temple of Jupiter Amun (Greek Ἄμμων *Ammon*).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Nevertheless, that salt ultimately gave ammonia and ammonium compounds their name.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] The earliest mention of ammonium chloride was in 554 in China.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] (Indeed, the word for ammonium chloride in several Asian languages derives from the Iranian phrase *anosh adur* (immortal fire), a reference to the underground fires.) Ammonium chloride was then transported along the Silk Road eastwards to China and westwards to the Muslim lands and Europe.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Around 800 A.D. the Persian chemist Jabir ibn Hayyan discovered ammonium chloride in the soot that resulted from burning camel dung, and this source became an alternative to those in Central Asia.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] The Jabirian alchemists were the authors of the Jabirian corpus, tentatively dated to c.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] The word for ammonium chloride in the Jabirian corpus was *nošāder*, Arabian in origin.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] Whereas Greek alchemical texts had been almost exclusively focused on the use of mineral substances, Jabirian alchemy pioneered the use of vegetable and animal substances, and so represented an innovative shift towards 'organic chemistry'.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] In the Jabirian corpus, the production of ammonium chloride from organic substances (such as plants, blood, and hair) is described.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] These are the oldest known instructions for deriving an inorganic compound from organic substances by chemical means.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] One of the innovations in Jabirian alchemy was the addition of ammonium chloride to the category of chemical substances known as 'spirits' (i.e., strongly volatile substances).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] This included both naturally occurring sal ammoniac and synthetic ammonium chloride produced from organic substances.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/ammonium-chloride] The addition of sal ammoniac to the list of 'spirits' can perhaps also be seen as a product of this new focus on organic chemistry.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] In the history of science, **pneumatic chemistry** is an area of scientific research of the seventeenth, eighteenth, and early nineteenth centuries.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Important goals of this work were the understanding of the physical properties of gases and how they relate to chemical reactions and, ultimately, the composition of matter.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] The rise of phlogiston theory, and its replacement by a new theory after the discovery of oxygen as a gaseous component of the Earth atmosphere and a chemical reagent participating in the combustion reactions, were addressed in the era of pneumatic chemistry.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] In the eighteenth century, as the field of chemistry was evolving from alchemy, a field of the natural philosophy was created around the idea of air as a reagent.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Before this, air was primarily considered a static substance that would not react and simply existed.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] However, as Lavoisier and several other pneumatic chemists would insist, the air was indeed dynamic, and would not only be influenced by combusted material, but would also influence the properties of different substances.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] The initial concern of pneumatic chemistry was combustion reactions, beginning with Stephen Hales.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] These reactions would give off different "airs" as chemists would call them, and these different airs contained more simple substances.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Until Lavoisier, these airs were considered separate entities with different properties; Lavoisier was responsible largely for changing the idea of air as being constituted by these different airs that his contemporaries and earlier chemists had discovered.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] This study of gases was brought about by Hales with the invention of the pneumatic trough, an instrument capable of collecting the gas given off by reactions with reproducible results.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] B. van Helmont, in the early seventeenth century.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] This term was derived from the Ancient Greek word *χάος, chaos*, as a result of his inability to collect properly the substances given off by reactions, as he was the first natural philosopher to make an attempt at carefully studying the third type of matter.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] However, it was not until Lavoisier performed his research in the eighteenth century that the word was used universally by scientists as a replacement for *airs*.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Van Helmont (1579 – 1644) is sometimes considered the founder of pneumatic chemistry, as he was the first natural philosopher to take an interest in air as a reagent.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Alessandro Volta began investigating pneumatic chemistry in 1776 and argued that there were different types of inflammable air based on experiments on marsh gases.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Pneumatic chemists credited with discovering chemical elements include Joseph Priestley, Henry Cavendish, Joseph Black, Daniel Rutherford, and Carl Scheele.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Other individuals who investigated gases during this period include Robert Boyle, Stephen Hales, William Brownrigg, Antoine Lavoisier, Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac, and John Dalton.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] The pneumatic trough was integral to the work with gases (or, as contemporary chemists called them, airs).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Work done by Joseph Black, Joseph Priestley, Herman Boerhaave, and Henry Cavendish revolved largely around the use of the instrument, allowing them to collect airs given off by different chemical reactions and combustion analyses.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Their work led to the discovery of many types of airs, such as dephlogisticated air (discovered by Joseph Priestley).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Moreover, the chemistry of airs was not limited to combustion analyses.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] During the eighteenth century, many chymists used the discovery of airs as a new path for exploring old problems, with one example being the field of medicinal chemistry.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] One particular Englishman, James Watt, began to take the idea of airs and use them in what was referred to as *pneumatic therapy*, or the use of airs to make laboratories more workable with fresh airs and also aid patients with different illnesses, with varying degrees of success.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Most human experimentation done was performed on the chymists themselves, as they believed that self-experimentation was a necessary part or progressing the field.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] James Watt's research in pneumatic chemistry involved the use of inflammable (H2) and dephlogisticated (O2) airs to create water.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] In 1783, James Watt showed that water was composed of inflammable and dephlogisticated airs, and that the masses of gases before combustion were exactly equal to the mass of water after combustion.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Until this point, water was viewed as a fundamental element rather than a compound.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] James Watt also sought to explore the use of different "factitious airs" such as hydrocarbonate in medicinal treatments as "pneumatic therapy" by collaborating with Dr.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Thomas Beddoes and Erasmus Darwin to treat Jessie Watt, his daughter suffering from tuberculosis, using fixed air.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Joseph Black was a chemist who took interest in the pneumatic field after studying under William Cullen.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] He was first interested in the topic of magnesia alba, or magnesium carbonate (MgCO3), and limestone, or calcium carbonate (CaCO3), and wrote a dissertation called "*De humore acido a cibis orto, et magnesia alba*" on the properties of both.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] His experiments on magnesium carbonate led him to discover that fixed air, or carbon dioxide (CO2), was being given off during reactions with various chemicals, including breathing.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Despite him never using the pneumatic trough or other instrumentation invented to collect and analyze the airs, his inferences led to more research into fixed air instead of common air, with the trough actually being used.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Joseph Priestley, in *Observations on different kinds of air,* was one of the first people to describe air as being composed of different states of matter, and not as one element.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Priestley elaborated on the notions of fixed air (CO2), mephitic air and inflammable air to include "inflammable nitrous air," "vitriolic acid air," "alkaline air" and "dephlogisticated air".
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Priestley also described the process of respiration in terms of phlogiston theory.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Priestley also established a process for treating scurvy and other ailments using fixed air in his *Directions for impregnating water with fixed air.* Priestley's work on pneumatic chemistry had an influence on his natural world views.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] His belief in an "aerial economy" stemmed from his belief in "dephlogisticated air" being the purest type of air and that phlogiston and combustion were at the heart of nature.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Joseph Priestley chiefly researched with the pneumatic trough, but he was responsible for collecting several new water-soluble airs.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] This was achieved primarily by his substitution of mercury for water, and implementing a shelf under the head for increased stability, capitalizing on the idea Cavendish proposed and popularizing the mercury pneumatic trough.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] While not credited for direct research into the field of pneumatic chemistry, Boerhaave (teacher, researcher, and scholar) did publish the *Elementa Chimiae* in 1727.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] This treatise included support for Hales' work and also elaborated upon the idea of airs.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Despite not publishing his own research, this section on airs in the *Elementa Chimiae* was cited by many other contemporaries and contained much of the current knowledge of the properties of airs.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Henry Cavendish, despite not being the first to replace water in the trough with mercury, was among the first to observe that fixed air was insoluble over mercury and therefore could be collected more efficiently using the adapted instrument.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] He also characterized fixed air (CO2) and inflammable air (H2).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Inflammable air was one of the first gases isolated and discovered using the pneumatic trough.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] However, he did not exploit his own idea to its limit, and therefore did not use the mercury pneumatic trough to its full extent.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Cavendish is credited with nearly correctly analyzing the content of gases in the atmosphere.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Cavendish also showed that inflammable air and atmospheric air could be combined and heated to produce water in 1784.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Hales was successful in preventing the air from losing its "elasticity," i.e. preventing it from experiencing a loss in volume, by bubbling the gas through water, and therefore dissolving the soluble gases.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] After the invention of the pneumatic trough, Stephen Hales continued his research into the different airs, and performed many Newtonian analyses of the various properties of them.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] He published his book *Vegetable Staticks* in 1727, which had a profound impact on the field of pneumatic chemistry, as many researchers cited this in their academic papers.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] In *Vegetable Staticks*, Hales not only introduced his trough, but also published the results he obtained from the collected air, such as the elasticity and composition of airs along with their ability to mix with others.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Stephen Hales, called the creator of pneumatic chemistry, created the pneumatic trough in 1727.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] This instrument was widely used by many chemists to explore the properties of different airs, such as what was called inflammable air (what is modernly called hydrogen).
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] Lavoisier used this in addition to his gasometer to collect gases and analyze them, aiding him in creating his list of simple substances.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] The pneumatic trough, while integral throughout the eighteenth century, was modified several times to collect gases more efficiently or just to collect more gas.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] For example, Cavendish noted that the amount of fixed air that was given off by a reaction was not entirely present above the water; this meant that fixed water was absorbing some of this air, and could not be used quantitatively to collect that particular air.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] So, he replaced the water in the trough with mercury instead, in which most airs were not soluble.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] By doing so, he could not only collect all airs given off by a reaction, but he could also determine the solubility of airs in water, beginning a new area of research for pneumatic chemists.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] While this was the major adaptation of the trough in the eighteenth century, several minor changes were made before and after this substitution of mercury for water, such as adding a shelf to rest the head on while gas collection occurred.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] This shelf would also allow for less conventional heads to be used, such as Brownrigg's animal bladder.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] A practical application of a pneumatic trough was the eudiometer, which was used by Jan Ingenhousz to show that plants produced dephlogisticated air when exposed to sunlight, a process now called photosynthesis.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] During his chemical revolution, Lavoisier created a new instrument for precisely measuring out gases.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] He called this instrument the *gazomètre*.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] He had two different versions; the one he used in demonstrations to the Académie and to the public, which was a large expensive version meant to make people believe that it had a large precision, and the smaller, more lab practical, version with a similar precision.
[src:pneumatic-chemistry/pneumatic-chemistry] This more practical version was cheaper to construct, allowing more chemists to use Lavoisier's instrument.
